imv.description: The MIB module to describe GE Digital Energy Uninterruptible Power Supplies.

PositiveInteger32.name: PositiveInteger32
PositiveInteger32.description: This data type is a non-zero and non-negative value.

NonNegativeInteger32.name: NonNegativeInteger32
NonNegativeInteger32.description: This data type is a non-negative value.

geDiscoveredUPSsMask.name: geDiscoveredUPSsMask
geDiscoveredUPSsMask.description: Reading this variable returns bit mask indicating which UPSs in a parallel system are alive. Management software should poll only these UPSs on their snmp branches 11-18 as follows: 1 FirstUPS alive 2 SecondUPS alive 4 ThirdUPS alive 8 FourthUPS alive 16 FifthUPS alive 32 SixthUPS alive 64 SeventhUPS alive 128 EigthUPS alive Since the management software should always monitor the GenericUPS branch (10), this value has no meaning for single upses (which provide values on that snmp branch), and should be set to zero in that case.

geRequestPacket.name: geRequestPacket
geRequestPacket.description: Put the string, formatted as a IMV/CP4 packet, directly to internally RS485 bus. This OID could be used for accede directly to the internally RS485 bus from a remote place.

geReplyPacket.name: geReplyPacket
geReplyPacket.description: Contain the reply of the IMV/CP4 request packet sent using the OID geRequestPacket. Every time that a write command has be made at the OID ge RequestPacket, the value of this OID is erased.

upsIdentManufacturer.name: upsIdentManufacturer
upsIdentManufacturer.description: The name of the UPS manufacturer.(*)

upsIdentUPSSoftwareVersion.name: upsIdentUPSSoftwareVersion
upsIdentUPSSoftwareVersion.description: The UPS firmware/software version(s). This variable may or may not have the same value as upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersion in some implementations.(*)

upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersion.name: upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersion
upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersion.description: The UPS agent software version. This variable may or may not have the same value as upsIdentUPSSoftwareVersion in some implementations.(*)

upsIdentName.name: upsIdentName
upsIdentName.description: A string identifying the UPS. This object should be set by the administrator.(*)

upsIdentAttachedDevices.name: upsIdentAttachedDevices
upsIdentAttachedDevices.description: A string identifying the devices attached to the output(s) of the UPS. This object should be set by the administrator.(*)

upsIdentOperatingTime.name: upsIdentOperatingTime
upsIdentOperatingTime.description: The present value of the operating time. total 'on' time since UPS manufactured

upsBatteryStatus.name: upsBatteryStatus
upsBatteryStatus.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsSecondsOnBattery.name: upsSecondsOnBattery
upsSecondsOnBattery.description: If the unit is on battery power, the elapsed time since the UPS last switched to battery power, or the time since the network management subsystem was last restarted, whichever is less. Zero shall be returned if the unit is not on battery power.(*)

upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining.name: upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining
upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining.description: An estimate of the time to battery charge depletion under the present load conditions if the utility power is off and remains off, or if it were to be lost and remain off.(*)

upsEstimatedChargeRemaining.name: upsEstimatedChargeRemaining
upsEstimatedChargeRemaining.description: An estimate of the battery charge remaining expressed as a percent of full charge.(*)

upsBatteryVoltage.name: upsBatteryVoltage
upsBatteryVoltage.description: The magnitude of the present battery voltage.(*)

upsBatteryTemperature.name: upsBatteryTemperature
upsBatteryTemperature.description: The ambient temperature at or near the UPS Battery casing.(*)

upsBatteryRipple.name: upsBatteryRipple
upsBatteryRipple.description: The present DC link RMS voltage ripple.(*)

upsInputLineBads.name: upsInputLineBads
upsInputLineBads.description: A count of the number of times the input entered an out-of-tolerance condition as defined by the manufacturer. This count is incremented by one each time the input transitions from zero out-of-tolerance lines to one or more input lines out-of-tolerance.(*)

upsInputNumLines.name: upsInputNumLines
upsInputNumLines.description: The number of input lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the input table.(*)

upsInputTable.name: upsInputTable
upsInputTable.description: A list of input table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsInputNumLines.(*)

upsInputEntry.name: upsInputEntry
upsInputEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular input line.(*)

upsInputVoltage.name: upsInputVoltage
upsInputVoltage.description: The magnitude of the present input voltage.(*)

upsInputCurrent.name: upsInputCurrent
upsInputCurrent.description: The magnitude of the present input current.(*)

upsInputTruePower.name: upsInputTruePower
upsInputTruePower.description: The magnitude of the present input true power.(*)

upsInputVoltageMin.name: upsInputVoltageMin
upsInputVoltageMin.description: The lowest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsInputVoltageMax.name: upsInputVoltageMax
upsInputVoltageMax.description: The highest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsOutputSource.name: upsOutputSource
upsOutputSource.description: The present source of output power. The enumeration none(2) indicates that there is no source of output power (and therefore no output power), for example, the system has opened the output breaker.(*)

upsOutputNumLines.name: upsOutputNumLines
upsOutputNumLines.description: The number of output lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the output table.(*)

upsOutputTable.name: upsOutputTable
upsOutputTable.description: A list of output table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsOutputNumLines.(*)

upsOutputEntry.name: upsOutputEntry
upsOutputEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular output line.(*)

upsOutputPercentLoad.name: upsOutputPercentLoad
upsOutputPercentLoad.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactor.name: upsOutputPowerFactor
upsOutputPowerFactor.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrent.name: upsOutputShareCurrent
upsOutputShareCurrent.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLines.name: upsBypassNumLines
upsBypassNumLines.description: The number of bypass lines utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the bypass table.(*)

upsBypassTable.name: upsBypassTable
upsBypassTable.description: A list of bypass table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsBypassNumLines.(*)

upsBypassEntry.name: upsBypassEntry
upsBypassEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPower.name: upsBypassPower
upsBypassPower.description: The present true power conveyed by the bypass.(*)

upsAlarmsPresent.name: upsAlarmsPresent
upsAlarmsPresent.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmTable.name: upsAlarmTable
upsAlarmTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmEntry.name: upsAlarmEntry
upsAlarmEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmId.name: upsAlarmId
upsAlarmId.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescr.name: upsAlarmDescr
upsAlarmDescr.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTime.name: upsAlarmTime
upsAlarmTime.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmOnBattery.name: upsAlarmOnBattery
upsAlarmOnBattery.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.(*)

upsAlarmLowBattery.name: upsAlarmLowBattery
upsAlarmLowBattery.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.(*)

upsAlarmDepletedBattery.name: upsAlarmDepletedBattery
upsAlarmDepletedBattery.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost.(*)

upsAlarmTempBad.name: upsAlarmTempBad

upsAlarmInputBad.name: upsAlarmInputBad
upsAlarmInputBad.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBad.name: upsAlarmBypassBad
upsAlarmBypassBad.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequested.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequested

upsAlarmChargerFailed.name: upsAlarmChargerFailed

upsAlarmUpsOutputOff.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOff.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOff
upsAlarmUpsSystemOff.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailure.name: upsAlarmFanFailure

upsAlarmFuseFailure.name: upsAlarmFuseFailure
upsAlarmFuseFailure.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFault.name: upsAlarmGeneralFault

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailed.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailed

upsAlarmCommunicationsLost.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLost

upsAlarmAwaitingPower.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPower

upsAlarmShutdownImminent.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminent
upsAlarmShutdownImminent.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 seconds; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgress.name: upsAlarmTestInProgress
upsAlarmTestInProgress.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailure.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailure
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailure.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailure.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailure
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailure.description: A CRC problem on the Highspeed Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailure.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailure
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailure.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailure.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailure
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailure.description: A CRC problem on the Highspeed Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharing.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharing
upsAlarmCurrentSharing.description: The System detects an high current sharing on the parallel system

upsAlarmDCRipple.name: upsAlarmDCRipple
upsAlarmDCRipple.description: The System detects an high ripple voltage on one DC link

upsAlarmMaskA.name: upsAlarmMaskA
upsAlarmMaskA.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestId.name: upsTestId
upsTestId.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLock.name: upsTestSpinLock
upsTestSpinLock.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummary.name: upsTestResultsSummary
upsTestResultsSummary.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetail.name: upsTestResultsDetail
upsTestResultsDetail.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTime.name: upsTestStartTime
upsTestStartTime.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTime.name: upsTestElapsedTime
upsTestElapsedTime.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiated.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiated
upsTestNoTestsInitiated.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgress.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgress
upsTestAbortTestInProgress.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTest.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTest
upsTestGeneralSystemsTest.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTest.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTest
upsTestQuickBatteryTest.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibration.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibration
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibration.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownType.name: upsShutdownType
upsShutdownType.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelay.name: upsShutdownAfterDelay
upsShutdownAfterDelay.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of seconds, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of seconds remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelay.name: upsStartupAfterDelay
upsStartupAfterDelay.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of seconds, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of seconds until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDuration.name: upsRebootWithDuration
upsRebootWithDuration.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of seconds, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of seconds required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 seconds. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of seconds remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestart.name: upsAutoRestart
upsAutoRestart.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNum.name: upsReceptaclesNum
upsReceptaclesNum.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleTable.name: upsReceptacleTable
upsReceptacleTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleEntry.name: upsReceptacleEntry
upsReceptacleEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOff.name: upsReceptacleOnOff
upsReceptacleOnOff.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSMode.name: upsUPSMode
upsUPSMode.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOff.name: upsRectifierOnOff
upsRectifierOnOff.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethod.name: upsBatteryChargeMethod
upsBatteryChargeMethod.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOff.name: upsInverterOnOff
upsInverterOnOff.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOff.name: upsBypassOnOff
upsBypassOnOff.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSource.name: upsLoadSource
upsLoadSource.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltage.name: upsConfigInputVoltage
upsConfigInputVoltage.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreq.name: upsConfigInputFreq
upsConfigInputFreq.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltage.name: upsConfigOutputVoltage
upsConfigOutputVoltage.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreq.name: upsConfigOutputFreq
upsConfigOutputFreq.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVA.name: upsConfigOutputVA
upsConfigOutputVA.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPower.name: upsConfigOutputPower
upsConfigOutputPower.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTime.name: upsConfigLowBattTime
upsConfigLowBattTime.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatus.name: upsConfigAudibleStatus
upsConfigAudibleStatus.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPoint.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPoint
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPoint.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPoint.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPoint
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPoint.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacity.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacity
upsConfigBatteryCapacity.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrent.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrent
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrent.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdown.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdown
upsConfigNoLoadShutdown.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelay.name: upsConfigStartDelay
upsConfigStartDelay.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNext.name: upsEventGetNext
upsEventGetNext.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPrevious.name: upsEventGetPrevious
upsEventGetPrevious.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp
upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStamp.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStamp
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStamp.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSize.name: upsEventTableSize
upsEventTableSize.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventTable.name: upsEventTable
upsEventTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventEntry.name: upsEventEntry
upsEventEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCode.name: upsEventCode
upsEventCode.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatus.name: upsEventStatus
upsEventStatus.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTime.name: upsEventTime
upsEventTime.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersRead.name: upsParametersRead
upsParametersRead.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWrite.name: upsParametersWrite
upsParametersWrite.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the first value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddress.name: upsParametersStartAddress
upsParametersStartAddress.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSize.name: upsParameterTableSize
upsParameterTableSize.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterTable.name: upsParameterTable
upsParameterTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterEntry.name: upsParameterEntry
upsParameterEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValue.name: upsParameterValue
upsParameterValue.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatus.name: upsStatus
upsStatus.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsDiagnosticBatteryLifetime.description: The critical components are associated to Service parameters indicating the remaining lifetime. They are initially set to default values depending to the data given by the component supplier. The parameter values decrease over time and when one of them reaches zero (lifetime expiration) a service check warning is generated, indicating that a check or a replacement is suggested for that component. The service technician is then required to re-set the default value after the replacing of the component.(*)

upsIdentAttachedDevicesfirst.name: upsIdentAttachedDevicesfirst
upsIdentAttachedDevicesfirst.description: A string identifying the devices attached to the output(s) of the UPS. This object should be set by the administrator.(*)

upsIdentOperatingTimefirst.name: upsIdentOperatingTimefirst
upsIdentOperatingTimefirst.description: The present value of the operating time. total 'on' time since UPS manufactured

upsBatteryStatusfirst.name: upsBatteryStatusfirst
upsBatteryStatusfirst.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsSecondsOnBatteryfirst.name: upsSecondsOnBatteryfirst
upsSecondsOnBatteryfirst.description: If the unit is on battery power, the elapsed time since the UPS last switched to battery power, or the time since the network management subsystem was last restarted, whichever is less. Zero shall be returned if the unit is not on battery power.(*)

upsEstimatedMinutesRemainingfirst.name: upsEstimatedMinutesRemainingfirst

upsEstimatedChargeRemainingfirst.name: upsEstimatedChargeRemainingfirst

upsBatteryVoltagefirst.description: The magnitude of the present battery voltage.(*)

upsBatteryTemperaturefirst.name: upsBatteryTemperaturefirst

upsBatteryRipplefirst.name: upsBatteryRipplefirst

upsInputVoltageMaxfirst.name: upsInputVoltageMaxfirst

upsOutputSourcefirst.name: upsOutputSourcefirst
upsOutputSourcefirst.description: The present source of output power. The enumeration none(2) indicates that there is no source of output power (and therefore no output power), for example, the system has opened the output breaker.(*)

upsOutputNumLinesfirst.name: upsOutputNumLinesfirst
upsOutputNumLinesfirst.description: The number of output lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the output table.(*)

upsOutputFirstTable.name: upsOutputFirstTable
upsOutputFirstTable.description: A list of output table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsOutputNumLines.(*)

upsOutputFirstEntry.name: upsOutputFirstEntry

upsOutputPercentLoadfirst.name: upsOutputPercentLoadfirst
upsOutputPercentLoadfirst.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorfirst.name: upsOutputPowerFactorfirst
upsOutputPowerFactorfirst.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentfirst.name: upsOutputShareCurrentfirst
upsOutputShareCurrentfirst.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinesfirst.name: upsBypassNumLinesfirst
upsBypassNumLinesfirst.description: The number of bypass lines utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the bypass table.(*)

upsBypassFirstTable.name: upsBypassFirstTable
upsBypassFirstTable.description: A list of bypass table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsBypassNumLines.(*)

upsBypassFirstEntry.name: upsBypassFirstEntry
upsBypassFirstEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPowerfirst.name: upsBypassPowerfirst
upsBypassPowerfirst.description: The present true power conveyed by the bypass.(*)

upsAlarmsPresentfirst.name: upsAlarmsPresentfirst
upsAlarmsPresentfirst.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmFirstTable.name: upsAlarmFirstTable
upsAlarmFirstTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmFirstEntry.name: upsAlarmFirstEntry
upsAlarmFirstEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdfirst.name: upsAlarmIdfirst
upsAlarmIdfirst.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrfirst.name: upsAlarmDescrfirst
upsAlarmDescrfirst.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimefirst.name: upsAlarmTimefirst
upsAlarmTimefirst.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmBatteryBadfirst.name: upsAlarmBatteryBadfirst
upsAlarmBatteryBadfirst.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.(*)

upsAlarmOnBatteryfirst.name: upsAlarmOnBatteryfirst
upsAlarmOnBatteryfirst.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.(*)

upsAlarmLowBatteryfirst.name: upsAlarmLowBatteryfirst
upsAlarmLowBatteryfirst.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.(*)

upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfirst.name: upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfirst
upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfirst.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost.(*)

upsAlarmTempBadfirst.name: upsAlarmTempBadfirst
upsAlarmTempBadfirst.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmInputBadfirst.name: upsAlarmInputBadfirst
upsAlarmInputBadfirst.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputBadfirst.name: upsAlarmOutputBadfirst
upsAlarmOutputBadfirst.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOverloadfirst.name: upsAlarmOutputOverloadfirst
upsAlarmOutputOverloadfirst.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypassfirst.name: upsAlarmOnBypassfirst
upsAlarmOnBypassfirst.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadfirst.name: upsAlarmBypassBadfirst
upsAlarmBypassBadfirst.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfirst.name: upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfirst
upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfirst.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfirst.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfirst
upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfirst.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.(*)

upsAlarmChargerFailedfirst.name: upsAlarmChargerFailedfirst
upsAlarmChargerFailedfirst.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffirst.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffirst
upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffirst.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffirst.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffirst
upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffirst.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmFanFailurefirst
upsAlarmFanFailurefirst.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmFuseFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmFuseFailurefirst
upsAlarmFuseFailurefirst.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFaultfirst.name: upsAlarmGeneralFaultfirst
upsAlarmGeneralFaultfirst.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfirst.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfirst
upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfirst.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.(*)

upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfirst.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfirst
upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfirst.description: A problem has been encountered in the communications between the agent and the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfirst.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfirst
upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfirst.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of input power.(*)

upsAlarmShutdownImminentfirst.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminentfirst
upsAlarmShutdownImminentfirst.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 seconds; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgressfirst.name: upsAlarmTestInProgressfirst
upsAlarmTestInProgressfirst.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefirst
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefirst.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefirst
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefirst.description: A CRC failure on High Speed Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefirst
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefirst.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefirst.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefirst
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefirst.description: A CRC failure on High Speed Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharingfirst.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharingfirst
upsAlarmCurrentSharingfirst.description: The UPS detects an high current sharing on the parallel system.

upsAlarmDCRipplefirst.name: upsAlarmDCRipplefirst
upsAlarmDCRipplefirst.description: The UPS detects an high ripple voltage on his DC link.

upsAlarmMaskAfirst.name: upsAlarmMaskAfirst
upsAlarmMaskAfirst.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdfirst.name: upsTestIdfirst
upsTestIdfirst.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLockfirst.name: upsTestSpinLockfirst
upsTestSpinLockfirst.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummaryfirst.name: upsTestResultsSummaryfirst
upsTestResultsSummaryfirst.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailfirst.name: upsTestResultsDetailfirst
upsTestResultsDetailfirst.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimefirst.name: upsTestStartTimefirst
upsTestStartTimefirst.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimefirst.name: upsTestElapsedTimefirst
upsTestElapsedTimefirst.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfirst.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfirst
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfirst.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgressfirst.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgressfirst
upsTestAbortTestInProgressfirst.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfirst.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfirst
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfirst.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestfirst.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestfirst
upsTestQuickBatteryTestfirst.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfirst.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfirst
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfirst.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypefirst.name: upsShutdownTypefirst
upsShutdownTypefirst.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelayfirst.name: upsShutdownAfterDelayfirst
upsShutdownAfterDelayfirst.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of seconds, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of seconds remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelayfirst.name: upsStartupAfterDelayfirst
upsStartupAfterDelayfirst.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of seconds, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of seconds until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationfirst.name: upsRebootWithDurationfirst
upsRebootWithDurationfirst.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of seconds, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of seconds required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 seconds. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of seconds remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartfirst.name: upsAutoRestartfirst
upsAutoRestartfirst.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumfirst.name: upsReceptaclesNumfirst
upsReceptaclesNumfirst.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleFirstTable.name: upsReceptacleFirstTable
upsReceptacleFirstTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleFirstEntry.name: upsReceptacleFirstEntry
upsReceptacleFirstEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOfffirst.name: upsReceptacleOnOfffirst
upsReceptacleOnOfffirst.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModefirst.name: upsUPSModefirst
upsUPSModefirst.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOfffirst.name: upsRectifierOnOfffirst
upsRectifierOnOfffirst.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodfirst.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodfirst
upsBatteryChargeMethodfirst.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOfffirst.name: upsInverterOnOfffirst
upsInverterOnOfffirst.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOfffirst.name: upsBypassOnOfffirst
upsBypassOnOfffirst.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcefirst.name: upsLoadSourcefirst
upsLoadSourcefirst.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagefirst.name: upsConfigInputVoltagefirst
upsConfigInputVoltagefirst.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqfirst.name: upsConfigInputFreqfirst
upsConfigInputFreqfirst.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagefirst.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagefirst
upsConfigOutputVoltagefirst.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqfirst.name: upsConfigOutputFreqfirst
upsConfigOutputFreqfirst.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAfirst.name: upsConfigOutputVAfirst
upsConfigOutputVAfirst.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowerfirst.name: upsConfigOutputPowerfirst
upsConfigOutputPowerfirst.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimefirst.name: upsConfigLowBattTimefirst
upsConfigLowBattTimefirst.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatusfirst.name: upsConfigAudibleStatusfirst
upsConfigAudibleStatusfirst.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfirst.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfirst
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfirst.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfirst.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfirst
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfirst.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacityfirst.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacityfirst
upsConfigBatteryCapacityfirst.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfirst.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfirst
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfirst.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfirst.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfirst
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfirst.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelayfirst.name: upsConfigStartDelayfirst
upsConfigStartDelayfirst.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextfirst.name: upsEventGetNextfirst
upsEventGetNextfirst.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPreviousfirst.name: upsEventGetPreviousfirst
upsEventGetPreviousfirst.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfirst.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfirst
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfirst.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfirst.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfirst
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfirst.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizefirst.name: upsEventTableSizefirst
upsEventTableSizefirst.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventFirstTable.name: upsEventFirstTable
upsEventFirstTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventFirstEntry.name: upsEventFirstEntry
upsEventFirstEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodefirst.name: upsEventCodefirst
upsEventCodefirst.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatusfirst.name: upsEventStatusfirst
upsEventStatusfirst.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTimefirst.name: upsEventTimefirst
upsEventTimefirst.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersReadfirst.name: upsParametersReadfirst
upsParametersReadfirst.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWritefirst.name: upsParametersWritefirst
upsParametersWritefirst.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the first value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddressfirst.name: upsParametersStartAddressfirst
upsParametersStartAddressfirst.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizefirst.name: upsParameterTableSizefirst
upsParameterTableSizefirst.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterFirstTable.name: upsParameterFirstTable
upsParameterFirstTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterFirstEntry.name: upsParameterFirstEntry
upsParameterFirstEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValuefirst.name: upsParameterValuefirst
upsParameterValuefirst.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatusfirst.name: upsStatusfirst
upsStatusfirst.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsMainsStatisticsMBfailfirst.name: upsMainsStatisticsMBfailfirst
upsMainsStatisticsMBfailfirst.description: Count of main bypass failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsMRfailfirst.name: upsMainsStatisticsMRfailfirst
upsMainsStatisticsMRfailfirst.description: Count of mains rectifier failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsB2first.name: upsMainsStatisticsB2first
upsMainsStatisticsB2first.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (0..2 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB5first.name: upsMainsStatisticsB5first
upsMainsStatisticsB5first.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (2..5 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB10first.name: upsMainsStatisticsB10first
upsMainsStatisticsB10first.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (5..10 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB200first.name: upsMainsStatisticsB200first
upsMainsStatisticsB200first.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (10..200 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsBypRelfirst.name: upsMainsStatisticsBypRelfirst
upsMainsStatisticsBypRelfirst.description: Bypass reliability degree [0..100%;255]. The value NOSUCHNAME means 'not available'.

upsTimefirst.name: upsTimefirst
upsTimefirst.description: The current timestamp (or real-time) of the UPS. For the format, see 'Timestamp' specifications. The write-command has to comply with the correct timestamp format expected by the UPS (counter value or real-time-clock value). Missing to doing so will result in a SNMPfirstERROR, meaning 'command not supported'. It is possible to know which is the timestamp format supported by the UPS, by issuing a read-command or by reading events, which includes timestamps.

upsRequestPermissionfirst.name: upsRequestPermissionfirst
upsRequestPermissionfirst.description: An encrypted code is send to enable use of restricted write objects during a limited period of time.

upsDiagnosticBatteryLifetimefirst.description: The critical components are associated to Service parameters indicating the remaining lifetime. The service technician is then required to re-set the default value after the replacing of the component.(*)

upsBatteryStatussecond.name: upsBatteryStatussecond
upsBatteryStatussecond.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorsecond.name: upsOutputPowerFactorsecond
upsOutputPowerFactorsecond.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentsecond.name: upsOutputShareCurrentsecond
upsOutputShareCurrentsecond.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsAlarmSecondTable.name: upsAlarmSecondTable
upsAlarmSecondTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmSecondEntry.name: upsAlarmSecondEntry

upsAlarmIdsecond.name: upsAlarmIdsecond
upsAlarmIdsecond.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrsecond.name: upsAlarmDescrsecond

upsAlarmTimesecond.name: upsAlarmTimesecond
