upsAlarmMaskAsecond.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdsecond.name: upsTestIdsecond
upsTestIdsecond.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLocksecond.name: upsTestSpinLocksecond
upsTestSpinLocksecond.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummarysecond.name: upsTestResultsSummarysecond
upsTestResultsSummarysecond.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailsecond.name: upsTestResultsDetailsecond
upsTestResultsDetailsecond.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimesecond.name: upsTestStartTimesecond
upsTestStartTimesecond.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimesecond.name: upsTestElapsedTimesecond
upsTestElapsedTimesecond.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsecond.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsecond
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsecond.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgresssecond.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgresssecond
upsTestAbortTestInProgresssecond.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsecond.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsecond
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsecond.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestsecond.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestsecond
upsTestQuickBatteryTestsecond.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsecond.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsecond
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsecond.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypesecond.name: upsShutdownTypesecond
upsShutdownTypesecond.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelaysecond.name: upsShutdownAfterDelaysecond
upsShutdownAfterDelaysecond.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of seconds, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of seconds remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelaysecond.name: upsStartupAfterDelaysecond
upsStartupAfterDelaysecond.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of seconds, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of seconds until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationsecond.name: upsRebootWithDurationsecond
upsRebootWithDurationsecond.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of seconds, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of seconds required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 seconds. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of seconds remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartsecond.name: upsAutoRestartsecond
upsAutoRestartsecond.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumsecond.name: upsReceptaclesNumsecond
upsReceptaclesNumsecond.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleSecondTable.name: upsReceptacleSecondTable
upsReceptacleSecondTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleSecondEntry.name: upsReceptacleSecondEntry
upsReceptacleSecondEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOffsecond.name: upsReceptacleOnOffsecond
upsReceptacleOnOffsecond.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModesecond.name: upsUPSModesecond
upsUPSModesecond.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOffsecond.name: upsRectifierOnOffsecond
upsRectifierOnOffsecond.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodsecond.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodsecond
upsBatteryChargeMethodsecond.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOffsecond.name: upsInverterOnOffsecond
upsInverterOnOffsecond.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOffsecond.name: upsBypassOnOffsecond
upsBypassOnOffsecond.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcesecond.name: upsLoadSourcesecond
upsLoadSourcesecond.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagesecond.name: upsConfigInputVoltagesecond
upsConfigInputVoltagesecond.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqsecond.name: upsConfigInputFreqsecond
upsConfigInputFreqsecond.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagesecond.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagesecond
upsConfigOutputVoltagesecond.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqsecond.name: upsConfigOutputFreqsecond
upsConfigOutputFreqsecond.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAsecond.name: upsConfigOutputVAsecond
upsConfigOutputVAsecond.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowersecond.name: upsConfigOutputPowersecond
upsConfigOutputPowersecond.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimesecond.name: upsConfigLowBattTimesecond
upsConfigLowBattTimesecond.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatussecond.name: upsConfigAudibleStatussecond
upsConfigAudibleStatussecond.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsecond.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsecond
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsecond.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsecond.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsecond
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsecond.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacitysecond.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacitysecond
upsConfigBatteryCapacitysecond.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsecond.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsecond
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsecond.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsecond.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsecond
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsecond.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelaysecond.name: upsConfigStartDelaysecond
upsConfigStartDelaysecond.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextsecond.name: upsEventGetNextsecond
upsEventGetNextsecond.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPrevioussecond.name: upsEventGetPrevioussecond
upsEventGetPrevioussecond.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsecond.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsecond
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsecond.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsecond.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsecond
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsecond.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizesecond.name: upsEventTableSizesecond
upsEventTableSizesecond.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventSecondTable.name: upsEventSecondTable
upsEventSecondTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventSecondEntry.name: upsEventSecondEntry
upsEventSecondEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodesecond.name: upsEventCodesecond
upsEventCodesecond.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatussecond.name: upsEventStatussecond
upsEventStatussecond.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTimesecond.name: upsEventTimesecond
upsEventTimesecond.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersReadsecond.name: upsParametersReadsecond
upsParametersReadsecond.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWritesecond.name: upsParametersWritesecond
upsParametersWritesecond.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the second value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddresssecond.name: upsParametersStartAddresssecond
upsParametersStartAddresssecond.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizesecond.name: upsParameterTableSizesecond
upsParameterTableSizesecond.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterSecondTable.name: upsParameterSecondTable
upsParameterSecondTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterSecondEntry.name: upsParameterSecondEntry
upsParameterSecondEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValuesecond.name: upsParameterValuesecond
upsParameterValuesecond.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatussecond.name: upsStatussecond
upsStatussecond.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsMainsStatisticsMBfailsecond.name: upsMainsStatisticsMBfailsecond
upsMainsStatisticsMBfailsecond.description: Count of main bypass failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsMRfailsecond.name: upsMainsStatisticsMRfailsecond
upsMainsStatisticsMRfailsecond.description: Count of mains rectifier failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsB2second.name: upsMainsStatisticsB2second
upsMainsStatisticsB2second.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (0..2 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB5second.name: upsMainsStatisticsB5second
upsMainsStatisticsB5second.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (2..5 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB10second.name: upsMainsStatisticsB10second
upsMainsStatisticsB10second.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (5..10 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB200second.name: upsMainsStatisticsB200second
upsMainsStatisticsB200second.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (10..200 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsBypRelsecond.name: upsMainsStatisticsBypRelsecond
upsMainsStatisticsBypRelsecond.description: Bypass reliability degree [0..100%;255]. The value NOSUCHNAME means 'not available'.

upsTimesecond.name: upsTimesecond
upsTimesecond.description: The current timestamp (or real-time) of the UPS. For the format, see 'Timestamp' specifications. The write-command has to comply with the correct timestamp format expected by the UPS (counter value or real-time-clock value). Missing to doing so will result in a SNMPsecondERROR, meaning 'command not supported'. It is possible to know which is the timestamp format supported by the UPS, by issuing a read-command or by reading events, which includes timestamps.

upsRequestPermissionsecond.name: upsRequestPermissionsecond
upsRequestPermissionsecond.description: An encrypted code is send to enable use of restricted write objects during a limited period of time.

upsEventGetCodesecond.name: upsEventGetCodesecond
upsEventGetCodesecond.description: The code which is used as starting point to downloading the events from the UPS event buffer.

upsEventSpinLocksecond.name: upsEventSpinLocksecond
upsEventSpinLocksecond.description: A spin lock on the event subsystem.

upsParameterSpinLocksecond.name: upsParameterSpinLocksecond
upsParameterSpinLocksecond.description: A spin lock on the parameters subsystem.

upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadsecond
upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadsecond.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.

upsTrapAlarmOnBatterysecond.name: upsTrapAlarmOnBatterysecond
upsTrapAlarmOnBatterysecond.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.

upsTrapAlarmLowBatterysecond.name: upsTrapAlarmLowBatterysecond
upsTrapAlarmLowBatterysecond.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.

upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterysecond.name: upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterysecond
upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterysecond.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost)

upsTrapAlarmTempBadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmTempBadsecond
upsTrapAlarmTempBadsecond.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmInputBadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmInputBadsecond
upsTrapAlarmInputBadsecond.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputBadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputBadsecond
upsTrapAlarmOutputBadsecond.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadsecond
upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadsecond.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.

upsTrapAlarmOnBypasssecond.name: upsTrapAlarmOnBypasssecond
upsTrapAlarmOnBypasssecond.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.

upsTrapAlarmBypassBadsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmBypassBadsecond
upsTrapAlarmBypassBadsecond.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsecond
upsTrapAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsecond.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.

upsTrapAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsecond
upsTrapAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsecond.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.

upsTrapAlarmChargerFailedsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmChargerFailedsecond
upsTrapAlarmChargerFailedsecond.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.

upsTrapAlarmUpsOutputOffsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmUpsOutputOffsecond
upsTrapAlarmUpsOutputOffsecond.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.

upsTrapAlarmUpsSystemOffsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmUpsSystemOffsecond
upsTrapAlarmUpsSystemOffsecond.description: The UPS system is in the off state.

upsTrapAlarmFanFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmFanFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmFanFailuresecond.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.

upsTrapAlarmFuseFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmFuseFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmFuseFailuresecond.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.

upsTrapAlarmGeneralFaultsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmGeneralFaultsecond
upsTrapAlarmGeneralFaultsecond.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.

upsTrapAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsecond
upsTrapAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsecond.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.

upsTrapAlarmCommunicationsLostsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmCommunicationsLostsecond
upsTrapAlarmCommunicationsLostsecond.description: A problem has been encountered in the communication between the agent and the UPS.

upsTrapAlarmAwaitingPowersecond.name: upsTrapAlarmAwaitingPowersecond
upsTrapAlarmAwaitingPowersecond.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of the input power (*).

upsTrapAlarmShutdownImminentsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmShutdownImminentsecond
upsTrapAlarmShutdownImminentsecond.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 seconds; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.

upsTrapAlarmTestInProgresssecond.name: upsTrapAlarmTestInProgresssecond
upsTrapAlarmTestInProgresssecond.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.

upsTrapAlarmReceptacleOffsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmReceptacleOffsecond
upsTrapAlarmReceptacleOffsecond.description: A receptacle has been switched off.

upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusFailuresecond.description: A problem on the Highspeed Bus communication is detected.

upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJACRCFailureseco.name: upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJACRCFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJACRCFailureseco.description: A CRC failure on the Highspeed Bus JA is detected.

upsTrapAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresecond.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJBCRCFailureseco.name: upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJBCRCFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJBCRCFailureseco.description: A CRC failure on the Highspeed Bus JB is detected.

upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailuresecond.description: An high current sharing on the parallel system is detected.

upsTrapAlarmDCRippleFailuresecond.name: upsTrapAlarmDCRippleFailuresecond
upsTrapAlarmDCRippleFailuresecond.description: An high ripple voltage on his DC link is detected.

upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadRestoredsecond.name: upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadRestoredsecond
upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadRestoredsecond.description: A Battery bad condition is restored.

The service technician is then required to re-set the default value after the replacing of the component.(*)

upsBatteryStatusthird.name: upsBatteryStatusthird
upsBatteryStatusthird.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsSecondsOnBatterythird.name: upsSecondsOnBatterythird
upsSecondsOnBatterythird.description: If the unit is on battery power, the elapsed time since the UPS last switched to battery power, or the time since the network management subsystem was last restarted, whichever is less. Zero shall be returned if the unit is not on battery power.(*)

upsInputVoltageMaxthird.name: upsInputVoltageMaxthird

upsOutputSourcethird.name: upsOutputSourcethird
upsOutputSourcethird.description: The present source of output power. The enumeration none(2) indicates that there is no source of output power (and therefore no output power), for example, the system has opened the output breaker.(*)

upsOutputNumLinesthird.name: upsOutputNumLinesthird

upsOutputThirdTable.name: upsOutputThirdTable

upsOutputPercentLoadthird.name: upsOutputPercentLoadthird
upsOutputPercentLoadthird.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorthird.name: upsOutputPowerFactorthird
upsOutputPowerFactorthird.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentthird.name: upsOutputShareCurrentthird
upsOutputShareCurrentthird.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinesthird.name: upsBypassNumLinesthird

upsBypassThirdTable.name: upsBypassThirdTable

upsBypassThirdEntry.name: upsBypassThirdEntry
upsBypassThirdEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPowerthird.name: upsBypassPowerthird
upsBypassPowerthird.description: The present true power conveyed by the bypass.(*)

upsAlarmsPresentthird.name: upsAlarmsPresentthird
upsAlarmsPresentthird.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmThirdTable.name: upsAlarmThirdTable
upsAlarmThirdTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmThirdEntry.name: upsAlarmThirdEntry
upsAlarmThirdEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdthird.name: upsAlarmIdthird
upsAlarmIdthird.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrthird.name: upsAlarmDescrthird
upsAlarmDescrthird.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimethird.name: upsAlarmTimethird
upsAlarmTimethird.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypassthird.name: upsAlarmOnBypassthird
upsAlarmOnBypassthird.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadthird.name: upsAlarmBypassBadthird
upsAlarmBypassBadthird.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedthird.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedthird.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedthird

upsAlarmChargerFailedthird.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOffthird.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOffthird

upsAlarmFuseFailurethird.name: upsAlarmFuseFailurethird

upsAlarmShutdownImminentthird.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 seconds; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurethird.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurethird
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurethird.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurethird.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurethird
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurethird.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurethird.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurethird
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurethird.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurethird.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurethird

upsAlarmDCRipplethird.name: upsAlarmDCRipplethird

upsAlarmMaskAthird.name: upsAlarmMaskAthird
upsAlarmMaskAthird.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdthird.name: upsTestIdthird
upsTestIdthird.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLockthird.name: upsTestSpinLockthird
upsTestSpinLockthird.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummarythird.name: upsTestResultsSummarythird
upsTestResultsSummarythird.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailthird.name: upsTestResultsDetailthird
upsTestResultsDetailthird.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimethird.name: upsTestStartTimethird
upsTestStartTimethird.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimethird.name: upsTestElapsedTimethird
upsTestElapsedTimethird.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedthird.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedthird
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedthird.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgressthird.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgressthird
upsTestAbortTestInProgressthird.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestthird.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestthird
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestthird.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestthird.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestthird
upsTestQuickBatteryTestthird.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationthird.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationthird
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationthird.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypethird.name: upsShutdownTypethird
upsShutdownTypethird.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelaythird.name: upsShutdownAfterDelaythird
upsShutdownAfterDelaythird.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of Seconds, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of seconds remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelaythird.name: upsStartupAfterDelaythird
upsStartupAfterDelaythird.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of seconds, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of seconds until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationthird.name: upsRebootWithDurationthird
upsRebootWithDurationthird.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of seconds, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of seconds required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 seconds. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of seconds remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartthird.name: upsAutoRestartthird
upsAutoRestartthird.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumthird.name: upsReceptaclesNumthird
upsReceptaclesNumthird.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleThirdTable.name: upsReceptacleThirdTable
upsReceptacleThirdTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleThirdEntry.name: upsReceptacleThirdEntry
upsReceptacleThirdEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOffthird.name: upsReceptacleOnOffthird
upsReceptacleOnOffthird.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModethird.name: upsUPSModethird
upsUPSModethird.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOffthird.name: upsRectifierOnOffthird
upsRectifierOnOffthird.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodthird.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodthird
upsBatteryChargeMethodthird.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOffthird.name: upsInverterOnOffthird
upsInverterOnOffthird.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOffthird.name: upsBypassOnOffthird
upsBypassOnOffthird.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcethird.name: upsLoadSourcethird
upsLoadSourcethird.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagethird.name: upsConfigInputVoltagethird
upsConfigInputVoltagethird.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqthird.name: upsConfigInputFreqthird
upsConfigInputFreqthird.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagethird.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagethird
upsConfigOutputVoltagethird.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqthird.name: upsConfigOutputFreqthird
upsConfigOutputFreqthird.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAthird.name: upsConfigOutputVAthird
upsConfigOutputVAthird.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowerthird.name: upsConfigOutputPowerthird
upsConfigOutputPowerthird.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimethird.name: upsConfigLowBattTimethird
upsConfigLowBattTimethird.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatusthird.name: upsConfigAudibleStatusthird
upsConfigAudibleStatusthird.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointthird.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointthird
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointthird.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointthird.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointthird
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointthird.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacitythird.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacitythird
upsConfigBatteryCapacitythird.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentthird.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentthird
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentthird.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownthird.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownthird
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownthird.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelaythird.name: upsConfigStartDelaythird
upsConfigStartDelaythird.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextthird.name: upsEventGetNextthird
upsEventGetNextthird.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPreviousthird.name: upsEventGetPreviousthird
upsEventGetPreviousthird.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampthird.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampthird
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampthird.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampthird.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampthird
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampthird.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizethird.name: upsEventTableSizethird
upsEventTableSizethird.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventThirdTable.name: upsEventThirdTable
upsEventThirdTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventThirdEntry.name: upsEventThirdEntry
upsEventThirdEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodethird.name: upsEventCodethird
upsEventCodethird.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatusthird.name: upsEventStatusthird
upsEventStatusthird.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTimethird.name: upsEventTimethird
upsEventTimethird.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersReadthird.name: upsParametersReadthird
upsParametersReadthird.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWritethird.name: upsParametersWritethird
upsParametersWritethird.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the third value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddressthird.name: upsParametersStartAddressthird
upsParametersStartAddressthird.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizethird.name: upsParameterTableSizethird
upsParameterTableSizethird.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterThirdTable.name: upsParameterThirdTable
upsParameterThirdTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterThirdEntry.name: upsParameterThirdEntry
upsParameterThirdEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValuethird.name: upsParameterValuethird
upsParameterValuethird.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatusthird.name: upsStatusthird
upsStatusthird.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsMainsStatisticsMBfailthird.description: Count of main bypass failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsMRfailthird.name: upsMainsStatisticsMRfailthird
upsMainsStatisticsMRfailthird.description: Count of mains rectifier failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsB2third.name: upsMainsStatisticsB2third
upsMainsStatisticsB2third.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (0..2 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB5third.name: upsMainsStatisticsB5third
upsMainsStatisticsB5third.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (2..5 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB10third.name: upsMainsStatisticsB10third
upsMainsStatisticsB10third.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (5..10 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB200third.name: upsMainsStatisticsB200third
upsMainsStatisticsB200third.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (10..200 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsBypRelthird.name: upsMainsStatisticsBypRelthird
upsMainsStatisticsBypRelthird.description: Bypass reliability degree [0..100%;255]. The value NOSUCHNAME means 'not available'.

upsTimethird.name: upsTimethird
upsTimethird.description: The current timestamp (or real-time) of the UPS. For the format, see 'Timestamp' specifications. The write-command has to comply with the correct timestamp format expected by the UPS (counter value or real-time-clock value). Missing to doing so will result in a SNMP second ERROR, meaning 'command not supported'. It is possible to know which is the timestamp format supported by the UPS, by issuing a read-command or by reading events, which includes timestamps.

upsRequestPermissionthird.name: upsRequestPermissionthird
upsRequestPermissionthird.description: An encrypted code is send to enable use of restricted write objects during a limited period of time.

upsEventGetCodethird.name: upsEventGetCodethird
upsEventGetCodethird.description: The code which is used as starting point to downloading the events from the UPS event buffer.

upsEventSpinLockthird.name: upsEventSpinLockthird
upsEventSpinLockthird.description: A spin lock on the event subsystem.

upsParameterSpinLockthird.name: upsParameterSpinLockthird
upsParameterSpinLockthird.description: A spin lock on the parameters subsystem.

upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadthird.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.

upsTrapAlarmOnBatterythird.name: upsTrapAlarmOnBatterythird
upsTrapAlarmOnBatterythird.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.

upsTrapAlarmLowBatterythird.name: upsTrapAlarmLowBatterythird
upsTrapAlarmLowBatterythird.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.

upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterythird.name: upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterythird
upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatterythird.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost)

upsTrapAlarmTempBadthird.name: upsTrapAlarmTempBadthird
upsTrapAlarmTempBadthird.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmInputBadthird.name: upsTrapAlarmInputBadthird
upsTrapAlarmInputBadthird.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputBadthird.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputBadthird
upsTrapAlarmOutputBadthird.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadthird.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadthird

upsTrapAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedthird.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.

upsTrapAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedthird.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.

upsTrapAlarmChargerFailedthird.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.

upsTrapAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedthird.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.

upsTrapAlarmCommunicationsLostthird.name: upsTrapAlarmCommunicationsLostthird

upsTrapAlarmHighspeedBusJBCRCFailurethir.description: A CRC failure on the Highspeed Bus JB is detected.

upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailurethird.name: upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailurethird
upsTrapAlarmCurrentSharingFailurethird.description: An high current sharing on the parallel system is detected.

upsTrapAlarmDCRippleFailurethird.description: An high ripple voltage on his DC link is detected.

upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadRestoredthird.description: A Battery bad condition is restored.

upsTrapAlarmOnBatteryRestoredthird.description: The UPS is drawing power from mains again.

upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatteryRestoredthird.description: A Depleted Battery condition is restored.

The parameter values decrease over time and when one of them reaches zero (lifetime expiration) a service check warning is generated, indicating that a check or a replacement is suggested for that component. The service technician is then required to re-set the default value after the replacing of the component.(*)

upsIdentManufacturerfourth.description: The name of the UPS manufacturer.(*)
