upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersionfourth.name: upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersionfourth
upsIdentAgentSoftwareVersionfourth.description: The UPS agent software version. This variable may or may not have the same value as upsIdentUPSSoftwareVersion in some implementations.(*)

upsIdentNamefourth.name: upsIdentNamefourth
upsIdentNamefourth.description: A string identifying the UPS. This object should be set by the administrator.(*)

upsIdentAttachedDevicesfourth.name: upsIdentAttachedDevicesfourth
upsIdentAttachedDevicesfourth.description: A string identifying the devices attached to the output(s) of the UPS. This object should be set by the administrator.(*)

upsIdentOperatingTimefourth.name: upsIdentOperatingTimefourth
upsIdentOperatingTimefourth.description: The present value of the operating time. total 'on' time since UPS manufactured

upsBatteryStatusfourth.name: upsBatteryStatusfourth
upsBatteryStatusfourth.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsSecondsOnBatteryfourth.name: upsSecondsOnBatteryfourth
upsSecondsOnBatteryfourth.description: If the unit is on battery power, the elapsed time since the UPS last switched to battery power, or the time since the network management subsystem was last restarted, whichever is less. Zero shall be returned if the unit is not on battery power.(*)

upsEstimatedMinutesRemainingfourth.name: upsEstimatedMinutesRemainingfourth
upsEstimatedMinutesRemainingfourth.description: An estimate of the time to battery charge depletion under the present load conditions if the utility power is off and remains off, or if it were to be lost and remain off.(*)

upsEstimatedChargeRemainingfourth.name: upsEstimatedChargeRemainingfourth
upsEstimatedChargeRemainingfourth.description: An estimate of the battery charge remaining expressed as a percent of full charge.(*)

upsBatteryVoltagefourth.name: upsBatteryVoltagefourth
upsBatteryVoltagefourth.description: The magnitude of the present battery voltage.(*)

upsBatteryTemperaturefourth.name: upsBatteryTemperaturefourth
upsBatteryTemperaturefourth.description: The ambient temperature at or near the UPS Battery casing.(*)

upsBatteryRipplefourth.name: upsBatteryRipplefourth
upsBatteryRipplefourth.description: The present DC link RMS voltage ripple.(*)

upsInputLineBadsfourth.name: upsInputLineBadsfourth
upsInputLineBadsfourth.description: A count of the number of times the input entered an out-of-tolerance condition as defined by the manufacturer. This count is incremented by one each time the input transitions from zero out-of-tolerance lines to one or more input lines out-of-tolerance.(*)

upsInputNumLinesfourth.name: upsInputNumLinesfourth
upsInputNumLinesfourth.description: The number of input lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the input table.(*)

upsInputFourthTable.name: upsInputFourthTable
upsInputFourthTable.description: A list of input table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsInputNumLines.(*)

upsInputFourthEntry.name: upsInputFourthEntry
upsInputFourthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular input line.(*)

upsInputVoltagefourth.name: upsInputVoltagefourth
upsInputVoltagefourth.description: The magnitude of the present input voltage.(*)

upsInputCurrentfourth.name: upsInputCurrentfourth
upsInputCurrentfourth.description: The magnitude of the present input current.(*)

upsInputTruePowerfourth.name: upsInputTruePowerfourth
upsInputTruePowerfourth.description: The magnitude of the present input true power.(*)

upsInputVoltageMinfourth.name: upsInputVoltageMinfourth
upsInputVoltageMinfourth.description: The lowest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsInputVoltageMaxfourth.name: upsInputVoltageMaxfourth
upsInputVoltageMaxfourth.description: The highest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsOutputSourcefourth.name: upsOutputSourcefourth
upsOutputSourcefourth.description: The present source of output power. The enumeration none(2) indicates that there is no source of output power (and therefore no output power), for example, the system has opened the output breaker.(*)

upsOutputNumLinesfourth.name: upsOutputNumLinesfourth
upsOutputNumLinesfourth.description: The number of output lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the output table.(*)

upsOutputFourthTable.name: upsOutputFourthTable
upsOutputFourthTable.description: A list of output table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsOutputNumLines.(*)

upsOutputFourthEntry.name: upsOutputFourthEntry
upsOutputFourthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular output line.(*)

upsOutputPercentLoadfourth.name: upsOutputPercentLoadfourth
upsOutputPercentLoadfourth.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorfourth.name: upsOutputPowerFactorfourth
upsOutputPowerFactorfourth.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentfourth.name: upsOutputShareCurrentfourth
upsOutputShareCurrentfourth.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinesfourth.name: upsBypassNumLinesfourth
upsBypassNumLinesfourth.description: The number of bypass lines utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the bypass table.(*)

upsBypassFourthTable.name: upsBypassFourthTable
upsBypassFourthTable.description: A list of bypass table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsBypassNumLines.(*)

upsBypassFourthEntry.name: upsBypassFourthEntry
upsBypassFourthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPowerfourth.name: upsBypassPowerfourth
upsBypassPowerfourth.description: The present true power conveyed by the bypass.(*)

upsAlarmsPresentfourth.name: upsAlarmsPresentfourth
upsAlarmsPresentfourth.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmFourthTable.name: upsAlarmFourthTable
upsAlarmFourthTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmFourthEntry.name: upsAlarmFourthEntry
upsAlarmFourthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdfourth.name: upsAlarmIdfourth
upsAlarmIdfourth.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrfourth.name: upsAlarmDescrfourth
upsAlarmDescrfourth.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimefourth.name: upsAlarmTimefourth
upsAlarmTimefourth.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmBatteryBadfourth.name: upsAlarmBatteryBadfourth
upsAlarmBatteryBadfourth.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.(*)

upsAlarmOnBatteryfourth.name: upsAlarmOnBatteryfourth
upsAlarmOnBatteryfourth.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.(*)

upsAlarmLowBatteryfourth.name: upsAlarmLowBatteryfourth
upsAlarmLowBatteryfourth.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.(*)

upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfourth.name: upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfourth
upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfourth.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost.(*)

upsAlarmTempBadfourth.name: upsAlarmTempBadfourth
upsAlarmTempBadfourth.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmInputBadfourth.name: upsAlarmInputBadfourth
upsAlarmInputBadfourth.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputBadfourth.name: upsAlarmOutputBadfourth
upsAlarmOutputBadfourth.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOverloadfourth.name: upsAlarmOutputOverloadfourth
upsAlarmOutputOverloadfourth.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypassfourth.name: upsAlarmOnBypassfourth
upsAlarmOnBypassfourth.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadfourth.name: upsAlarmBypassBadfourth
upsAlarmBypassBadfourth.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfourth.name: upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfourth
upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfourth.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfourth.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfourth
upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfourth.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.(*)

upsAlarmChargerFailedfourth.name: upsAlarmChargerFailedfourth
upsAlarmChargerFailedfourth.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffourth.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffourth
upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffourth.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffourth.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffourth
upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffourth.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmFanFailurefourth
upsAlarmFanFailurefourth.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmFuseFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmFuseFailurefourth
upsAlarmFuseFailurefourth.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFaultfourth.name: upsAlarmGeneralFaultfourth
upsAlarmGeneralFaultfourth.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfourth.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfourth
upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfourth.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.(*)

upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfourth.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfourth
upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfourth.description: A problem has been encountered in the communications between the agent and the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfourth.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfourth
upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfourth.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of input power.(*)

upsAlarmShutdownImminentfourth.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminentfourth
upsAlarmShutdownImminentfourth.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 fourths; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgressfourth.name: upsAlarmTestInProgressfourth
upsAlarmTestInProgressfourth.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefourth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefourth.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefourth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefourth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefourth
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefourth.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefourth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefourth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefourth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharingfourth.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharingfourth
upsAlarmCurrentSharingfourth.description: The UPS detects an high current sharing on the parallel system.

upsAlarmDCRipplefourth.name: upsAlarmDCRipplefourth
upsAlarmDCRipplefourth.description: The UPS detects an high ripple voltage on his DC link.

upsAlarmMaskAfourth.name: upsAlarmMaskAfourth
upsAlarmMaskAfourth.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdfourth.name: upsTestIdfourth
upsTestIdfourth.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLockfourth.name: upsTestSpinLockfourth
upsTestSpinLockfourth.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummaryfourth.name: upsTestResultsSummaryfourth
upsTestResultsSummaryfourth.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailfourth.name: upsTestResultsDetailfourth
upsTestResultsDetailfourth.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimefourth.name: upsTestStartTimefourth
upsTestStartTimefourth.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimefourth.name: upsTestElapsedTimefourth
upsTestElapsedTimefourth.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfourth.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfourth
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfourth.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgressfourth.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgressfourth
upsTestAbortTestInProgressfourth.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfourth.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfourth
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfourth.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestfourth.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestfourth
upsTestQuickBatteryTestfourth.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfourth.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfourth
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfourth.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypefourth.name: upsShutdownTypefourth
upsShutdownTypefourth.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelayfourth.name: upsShutdownAfterDelayfourth
upsShutdownAfterDelayfourth.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of fourths, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of fourths remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelayfourth.name: upsStartupAfterDelayfourth
upsStartupAfterDelayfourth.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of fourths, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of fourths until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationfourth.name: upsRebootWithDurationfourth
upsRebootWithDurationfourth.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of fourths, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of fourths required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 fourths. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of fourths remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartfourth.name: upsAutoRestartfourth
upsAutoRestartfourth.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumfourth.name: upsReceptaclesNumfourth
upsReceptaclesNumfourth.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleFourthTable.name: upsReceptacleFourthTable
upsReceptacleFourthTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleFourthEntry.name: upsReceptacleFourthEntry
upsReceptacleFourthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOfffourth.name: upsReceptacleOnOfffourth
upsReceptacleOnOfffourth.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModefourth.name: upsUPSModefourth
upsUPSModefourth.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOfffourth.name: upsRectifierOnOfffourth
upsRectifierOnOfffourth.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodfourth.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodfourth
upsBatteryChargeMethodfourth.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOfffourth.name: upsInverterOnOfffourth
upsInverterOnOfffourth.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOfffourth.name: upsBypassOnOfffourth
upsBypassOnOfffourth.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcefourth.name: upsLoadSourcefourth
upsLoadSourcefourth.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagefourth.name: upsConfigInputVoltagefourth
upsConfigInputVoltagefourth.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqfourth.name: upsConfigInputFreqfourth
upsConfigInputFreqfourth.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagefourth.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagefourth
upsConfigOutputVoltagefourth.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqfourth.name: upsConfigOutputFreqfourth

It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. upsParameterFourthTable.name: upsParameterFourthTable
upsParameterFourthTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsInputLineBadsfifth.description: A count of the number of times the input entered an out-of-tolerance condition as defined by the manufacturer. This count is incremented by one each time the input transitions from zero out-of-tolerance lines to one or more input lines out-of-tolerance.(*)

upsInputNumLinesfifth.name: upsInputNumLinesfifth
upsInputNumLinesfifth.description: The number of input lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the input table.(*)

upsInputFifthTable.name: upsInputFifthTable
upsInputFifthTable.description: A list of input table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsInputNumLines.(*)

upsInputFifthEntry.name: upsInputFifthEntry
upsInputFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular input line.(*)

upsInputVoltagefifth.name: upsInputVoltagefifth
upsInputVoltagefifth.description: The magnitude of the present input voltage.(*)

upsInputCurrentfifth.name: upsInputCurrentfifth
upsInputCurrentfifth.description: The magnitude of the present input current.(*)

upsInputTruePowerfifth.name: upsInputTruePowerfifth
upsInputTruePowerfifth.description: The magnitude of the present input true power.(*)

upsInputVoltageMinfifth.name: upsInputVoltageMinfifth
upsInputVoltageMinfifth.description: The lowest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsInputVoltageMaxfifth.name: upsInputVoltageMaxfifth
upsInputVoltageMaxfifth.description: The highest magnitude of the input voltage since last read out.

upsOutputSourcefifth.name: upsOutputSourcefifth
upsOutputSourcefifth.description: The present source of output power. The enumeration none(2) indicates that there is no source of output power (and therefore no output power), for example, the system has opened the output breaker.(*)

upsOutputNumLinesfifth.name: upsOutputNumLinesfifth
upsOutputNumLinesfifth.description: The number of output lines utilized in this device. This variable indicates the number of rows in the output table.(*)

upsOutputFifthTable.name: upsOutputFifthTable
upsOutputFifthTable.description: A list of output table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsOutputNumLines.(*)

upsOutputFifthEntry.name: upsOutputFifthEntry
upsOutputFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular output line.(*)

upsOutputPercentLoadfifth.name: upsOutputPercentLoadfifth
upsOutputPercentLoadfifth.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorfifth.name: upsOutputPowerFactorfifth
upsOutputPowerFactorfifth.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentfifth.name: upsOutputShareCurrentfifth
upsOutputShareCurrentfifth.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinesfifth.name: upsBypassNumLinesfifth
upsBypassNumLinesfifth.description: The number of bypass lines utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the bypass table.(*)

upsBypassFifthTable.name: upsBypassFifthTable
upsBypassFifthTable.description: A list of bypass table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsBypassNumLines.(*)

upsBypassFifthEntry.name: upsBypassFifthEntry
upsBypassFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPowerfifth.name: upsBypassPowerfifth
upsBypassPowerfifth.description: The present true power conveyed by the bypass.(*)

upsAlarmsPresentfifth.name: upsAlarmsPresentfifth
upsAlarmsPresentfifth.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmFifthTable.name: upsAlarmFifthTable
upsAlarmFifthTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmFifthEntry.name: upsAlarmFifthEntry
upsAlarmFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdfifth.name: upsAlarmIdfifth
upsAlarmIdfifth.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrfifth.name: upsAlarmDescrfifth
upsAlarmDescrfifth.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimefifth.name: upsAlarmTimefifth
upsAlarmTimefifth.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmBatteryBadfifth.name: upsAlarmBatteryBadfifth
upsAlarmBatteryBadfifth.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.(*)

upsAlarmOnBatteryfifth.name: upsAlarmOnBatteryfifth
upsAlarmOnBatteryfifth.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.(*)

upsAlarmLowBatteryfifth.name: upsAlarmLowBatteryfifth
upsAlarmLowBatteryfifth.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.(*)

upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfifth.name: upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfifth
upsAlarmDepletedBatteryfifth.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost.(*)

upsAlarmTempBadfifth.name: upsAlarmTempBadfifth
upsAlarmTempBadfifth.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmInputBadfifth.name: upsAlarmInputBadfifth
upsAlarmInputBadfifth.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputBadfifth.name: upsAlarmOutputBadfifth
upsAlarmOutputBadfifth.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOverloadfifth.name: upsAlarmOutputOverloadfifth
upsAlarmOutputOverloadfifth.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypassfifth.name: upsAlarmOnBypassfifth
upsAlarmOnBypassfifth.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadfifth.name: upsAlarmBypassBadfifth
upsAlarmBypassBadfifth.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfifth.name: upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfifth
upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedfifth.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfifth.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfifth
upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedfifth.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.(*)

upsAlarmChargerFailedfifth.name: upsAlarmChargerFailedfifth
upsAlarmChargerFailedfifth.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffifth.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffifth
upsAlarmUpsOutputOfffifth.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffifth.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffifth
upsAlarmUpsSystemOfffifth.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmFanFailurefifth
upsAlarmFanFailurefifth.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmFuseFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmFuseFailurefifth
upsAlarmFuseFailurefifth.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFaultfifth.name: upsAlarmGeneralFaultfifth
upsAlarmGeneralFaultfifth.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfifth.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfifth
upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedfifth.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.(*)

upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfifth.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfifth
upsAlarmCommunicationsLostfifth.description: A problem has been encountered in the communications between the agent and the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfifth.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfifth
upsAlarmAwaitingPowerfifth.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of input power.(*)

upsAlarmShutdownImminentfifth.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminentfifth
upsAlarmShutdownImminentfifth.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 fifths; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgressfifth.name: upsAlarmTestInProgressfifth
upsAlarmTestInProgressfifth.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefifth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailurefifth.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefifth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailurefifth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefifth
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailurefifth.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefifth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefifth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailurefifth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharingfifth.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharingfifth
upsAlarmCurrentSharingfifth.description: The UPS detects an high current sharing on the parallel system.

upsAlarmDCRipplefifth.name: upsAlarmDCRipplefifth
upsAlarmDCRipplefifth.description: The UPS detects an high ripple voltage on his DC link.

upsAlarmMaskAfifth.name: upsAlarmMaskAfifth
upsAlarmMaskAfifth.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdfifth.name: upsTestIdfifth
upsTestIdfifth.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLockfifth.name: upsTestSpinLockfifth
upsTestSpinLockfifth.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummaryfifth.name: upsTestResultsSummaryfifth
upsTestResultsSummaryfifth.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailfifth.name: upsTestResultsDetailfifth
upsTestResultsDetailfifth.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimefifth.name: upsTestStartTimefifth
upsTestStartTimefifth.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimefifth.name: upsTestElapsedTimefifth
upsTestElapsedTimefifth.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfifth.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfifth
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedfifth.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgressfifth.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgressfifth
upsTestAbortTestInProgressfifth.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfifth.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfifth
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestfifth.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestfifth.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestfifth
upsTestQuickBatteryTestfifth.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfifth.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfifth
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationfifth.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypefifth.name: upsShutdownTypefifth
upsShutdownTypefifth.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelayfifth.name: upsShutdownAfterDelayfifth
upsShutdownAfterDelayfifth.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of fifths, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of fifths remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelayfifth.name: upsStartupAfterDelayfifth
upsStartupAfterDelayfifth.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of fifths, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of fifths until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationfifth.name: upsRebootWithDurationfifth
upsRebootWithDurationfifth.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of fifths, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of fifths required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 fifths. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of fifths remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartfifth.name: upsAutoRestartfifth
upsAutoRestartfifth.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumfifth.name: upsReceptaclesNumfifth
upsReceptaclesNumfifth.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleFifthTable.name: upsReceptacleFifthTable
upsReceptacleFifthTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleFifthEntry.name: upsReceptacleFifthEntry
upsReceptacleFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOfffifth.name: upsReceptacleOnOfffifth
upsReceptacleOnOfffifth.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModefifth.name: upsUPSModefifth
upsUPSModefifth.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOfffifth.name: upsRectifierOnOfffifth
upsRectifierOnOfffifth.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodfifth.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodfifth
upsBatteryChargeMethodfifth.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOfffifth.name: upsInverterOnOfffifth
upsInverterOnOfffifth.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOfffifth.name: upsBypassOnOfffifth
upsBypassOnOfffifth.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcefifth.name: upsLoadSourcefifth
upsLoadSourcefifth.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagefifth.name: upsConfigInputVoltagefifth
upsConfigInputVoltagefifth.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqfifth.name: upsConfigInputFreqfifth
upsConfigInputFreqfifth.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagefifth.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagefifth
upsConfigOutputVoltagefifth.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqfifth.name: upsConfigOutputFreqfifth
upsConfigOutputFreqfifth.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAfifth.name: upsConfigOutputVAfifth
upsConfigOutputVAfifth.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowerfifth.name: upsConfigOutputPowerfifth
upsConfigOutputPowerfifth.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimefifth.name: upsConfigLowBattTimefifth
upsConfigLowBattTimefifth.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatusfifth.name: upsConfigAudibleStatusfifth
upsConfigAudibleStatusfifth.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfifth.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfifth
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointfifth.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfifth.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfifth
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointfifth.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacityfifth.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacityfifth
upsConfigBatteryCapacityfifth.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfifth.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfifth
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentfifth.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfifth.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfifth
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownfifth.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelayfifth.name: upsConfigStartDelayfifth
upsConfigStartDelayfifth.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextfifth.name: upsEventGetNextfifth
upsEventGetNextfifth.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPreviousfifth.name: upsEventGetPreviousfifth
upsEventGetPreviousfifth.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfifth.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfifth
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampfifth.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfifth.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfifth
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampfifth.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizefifth.name: upsEventTableSizefifth
upsEventTableSizefifth.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventFifthTable.name: upsEventFifthTable
upsEventFifthTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventFifthEntry.name: upsEventFifthEntry
upsEventFifthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodefifth.name: upsEventCodefifth
upsEventCodefifth.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatusfifth.name: upsEventStatusfifth
upsEventStatusfifth.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsParametersWritefifth.name: upsParametersWritefifth
upsParametersWritefifth.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the fifth value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddressfifth.name: upsParametersStartAddressfifth
upsParametersStartAddressfifth.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizefifth.name: upsParameterTableSizefifth
upsParameterTableSizefifth.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterFifthTable.name: upsParameterFifthTable
upsParameterFifthTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsStatusfifth.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. upsBatteryStatussixth.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorsixth.name: upsOutputPowerFactorsixth
upsOutputPowerFactorsixth.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentsixth.name: upsOutputShareCurrentsixth
upsOutputShareCurrentsixth.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinessixth.description: The number of bypass lines utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the bypass table.(*)
