upsAlarmsPresentsixth.description: The present number of active alarm conditions.(*)

upsAlarmSixthTable.name: upsAlarmSixthTable
upsAlarmSixthTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmSixthEntry.name: upsAlarmSixthEntry
upsAlarmSixthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdsixth.name: upsAlarmIdsixth
upsAlarmIdsixth.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrsixth.name: upsAlarmDescrsixth
upsAlarmDescrsixth.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimesixth.name: upsAlarmTimesixth
upsAlarmTimesixth.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmBatteryBadsixth.name: upsAlarmBatteryBadsixth
upsAlarmBatteryBadsixth.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.(*)

upsAlarmOnBatterysixth.name: upsAlarmOnBatterysixth
upsAlarmOnBatterysixth.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.(*)

upsAlarmLowBatterysixth.name: upsAlarmLowBatterysixth
upsAlarmLowBatterysixth.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.(*)

upsAlarmDepletedBatterysixth.name: upsAlarmDepletedBatterysixth
upsAlarmDepletedBatterysixth.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost.(*)

upsAlarmTempBadsixth.name: upsAlarmTempBadsixth
upsAlarmTempBadsixth.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmInputBadsixth.name: upsAlarmInputBadsixth
upsAlarmInputBadsixth.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputBadsixth.name: upsAlarmOutputBadsixth
upsAlarmOutputBadsixth.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOverloadsixth.name: upsAlarmOutputOverloadsixth
upsAlarmOutputOverloadsixth.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypasssixth.name: upsAlarmOnBypasssixth
upsAlarmOnBypasssixth.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadsixth.name: upsAlarmBypassBadsixth
upsAlarmBypassBadsixth.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsixth.name: upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsixth
upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedsixth.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsixth.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsixth
upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedsixth.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.(*)

upsAlarmChargerFailedsixth.name: upsAlarmChargerFailedsixth
upsAlarmChargerFailedsixth.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOffsixth.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOffsixth
upsAlarmUpsOutputOffsixth.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOffsixth.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOffsixth
upsAlarmUpsSystemOffsixth.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmFanFailuresixth
upsAlarmFanFailuresixth.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmFuseFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmFuseFailuresixth
upsAlarmFuseFailuresixth.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFaultsixth.name: upsAlarmGeneralFaultsixth
upsAlarmGeneralFaultsixth.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsixth.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsixth
upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedsixth.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.(*)

upsAlarmCommunicationsLostsixth.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLostsixth
upsAlarmCommunicationsLostsixth.description: A problem has been encountered in the communications between the agent and the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmAwaitingPowersixth.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPowersixth
upsAlarmAwaitingPowersixth.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of input power.(*)

upsAlarmShutdownImminentsixth.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminentsixth
upsAlarmShutdownImminentsixth.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 sixths; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgresssixth.name: upsAlarmTestInProgresssixth
upsAlarmTestInProgresssixth.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailuresixth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailuresixth.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailuresixth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailuresixth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresixth
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailuresixth.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailuresixth.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailuresixth
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailuresixth.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharingsixth.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharingsixth
upsAlarmCurrentSharingsixth.description: The UPS detects an high current sharing on the parallel system.

upsAlarmDCRipplesixth.name: upsAlarmDCRipplesixth
upsAlarmDCRipplesixth.description: The UPS detects an high ripple voltage on his DC link.

upsAlarmMaskAsixth.name: upsAlarmMaskAsixth
upsAlarmMaskAsixth.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdsixth.name: upsTestIdsixth
upsTestIdsixth.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLocksixth.name: upsTestSpinLocksixth
upsTestSpinLocksixth.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummarysixth.name: upsTestResultsSummarysixth
upsTestResultsSummarysixth.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailsixth.name: upsTestResultsDetailsixth
upsTestResultsDetailsixth.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimesixth.name: upsTestStartTimesixth
upsTestStartTimesixth.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimesixth.name: upsTestElapsedTimesixth
upsTestElapsedTimesixth.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsixth.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsixth
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedsixth.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgresssixth.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgresssixth
upsTestAbortTestInProgresssixth.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsixth.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsixth
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestsixth.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestsixth.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestsixth
upsTestQuickBatteryTestsixth.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsixth.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsixth
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationsixth.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypesixth.name: upsShutdownTypesixth
upsShutdownTypesixth.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelaysixth.name: upsShutdownAfterDelaysixth
upsShutdownAfterDelaysixth.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of sixths, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of sixths remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelaysixth.name: upsStartupAfterDelaysixth
upsStartupAfterDelaysixth.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of sixths, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of sixths until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationsixth.name: upsRebootWithDurationsixth
upsRebootWithDurationsixth.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of sixths, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of sixths required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 sixths. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of sixths remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartsixth.name: upsAutoRestartsixth
upsAutoRestartsixth.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumsixth.name: upsReceptaclesNumsixth
upsReceptaclesNumsixth.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleSixthTable.name: upsReceptacleSixthTable
upsReceptacleSixthTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleSixthEntry.name: upsReceptacleSixthEntry
upsReceptacleSixthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOffsixth.name: upsReceptacleOnOffsixth
upsReceptacleOnOffsixth.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModesixth.name: upsUPSModesixth
upsUPSModesixth.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOffsixth.name: upsRectifierOnOffsixth
upsRectifierOnOffsixth.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodsixth.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodsixth
upsBatteryChargeMethodsixth.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOffsixth.name: upsInverterOnOffsixth
upsInverterOnOffsixth.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOffsixth.name: upsBypassOnOffsixth
upsBypassOnOffsixth.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourcesixth.name: upsLoadSourcesixth
upsLoadSourcesixth.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltagesixth.name: upsConfigInputVoltagesixth
upsConfigInputVoltagesixth.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqsixth.name: upsConfigInputFreqsixth
upsConfigInputFreqsixth.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltagesixth.name: upsConfigOutputVoltagesixth
upsConfigOutputVoltagesixth.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqsixth.name: upsConfigOutputFreqsixth
upsConfigOutputFreqsixth.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAsixth.name: upsConfigOutputVAsixth
upsConfigOutputVAsixth.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowersixth.name: upsConfigOutputPowersixth
upsConfigOutputPowersixth.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimesixth.name: upsConfigLowBattTimesixth
upsConfigLowBattTimesixth.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatussixth.name: upsConfigAudibleStatussixth
upsConfigAudibleStatussixth.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsixth.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsixth
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointsixth.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsixth.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsixth
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointsixth.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacitysixth.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacitysixth
upsConfigBatteryCapacitysixth.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsixth.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsixth
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentsixth.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsixth.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsixth
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownsixth.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelaysixth.name: upsConfigStartDelaysixth
upsConfigStartDelaysixth.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextsixth.name: upsEventGetNextsixth
upsEventGetNextsixth.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPrevioussixth.name: upsEventGetPrevioussixth
upsEventGetPrevioussixth.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsixth.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsixth
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampsixth.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsixth.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsixth
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampsixth.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizesixth.name: upsEventTableSizesixth
upsEventTableSizesixth.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventSixthTable.name: upsEventSixthTable
upsEventSixthTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventSixthEntry.name: upsEventSixthEntry
upsEventSixthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodesixth.name: upsEventCodesixth
upsEventCodesixth.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatussixth.name: upsEventStatussixth
upsEventStatussixth.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTimesixth.name: upsEventTimesixth
upsEventTimesixth.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersReadsixth.name: upsParametersReadsixth
upsParametersReadsixth.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWritesixth.name: upsParametersWritesixth
upsParametersWritesixth.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the sixth value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddresssixth.name: upsParametersStartAddresssixth
upsParametersStartAddresssixth.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizesixth.name: upsParameterTableSizesixth
upsParameterTableSizesixth.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterSixthTable.name: upsParameterSixthTable
upsParameterSixthTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterSixthEntry.name: upsParameterSixthEntry
upsParameterSixthEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValuesixth.name: upsParameterValuesixth
upsParameterValuesixth.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatussixth.name: upsStatussixth
upsStatussixth.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsMainsStatisticsMBfailsixth.name: upsMainsStatisticsMBfailsixth

upsBatteryStatusseventh.name: upsBatteryStatusseventh
upsBatteryStatusseventh.description: The indication of the capacity remaining in the UPS system's batteries. A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsSecondsOnBatteryseventh.name: upsSecondsOnBatteryseventh
upsSecondsOnBatteryseventh.description: If the unit is on battery power, the elapsed time since the UPS last switched to battery power, or the time since the network management subsystem was last restarted, whichever is less. Zero shall be returned if the unit is not on battery power.(*)

upsOutputSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular output line.(*)

upsOutputPercentLoadseventh.name: upsOutputPercentLoadseventh
upsOutputPercentLoadseventh.description: The percentage of the UPS power capacity presently being used on this output line, i.e., the greater of the percent load of true power capacity and the percent load of VA.(*)

upsOutputPowerFactorseventh.name: upsOutputPowerFactorseventh
upsOutputPowerFactorseventh.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrentseventh.name: upsOutputShareCurrentseventh
upsOutputShareCurrentseventh.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsBypassNumLinesseventh.name: upsBypassNumLinesseventh

upsBypassSeventhTable.name: upsBypassSeventhTable

upsBypassSeventhEntry.name: upsBypassSeventhEntry
upsBypassSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular bypass input.(*)

upsBypassPowerseventh.name: upsBypassPowerseventh

upsAlarmsPresentseventh.name: upsAlarmsPresentseventh

upsAlarmSeventhTable.name: upsAlarmSeventhTable
upsAlarmSeventhTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)

upsAlarmSeventhEntry.name: upsAlarmSeventhEntry
upsAlarmSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular alarm.(*)

upsAlarmIdseventh.name: upsAlarmIdseventh
upsAlarmIdseventh.description: A unique identifier for an alarm condition. This value must remain constant.(*)

upsAlarmDescrseventh.name: upsAlarmDescrseventh
upsAlarmDescrseventh.description: A reference to an alarm description object. The object referenced should not be accessible, but rather be used to provide a unique description of the alarm condition.(*)

upsAlarmTimeseventh.name: upsAlarmTimeseventh
upsAlarmTimeseventh.description: The value of sysUpTime when the alarm condition was detected. If the alarm condition was detected at the time of agent startup and presumably existed before agent startup, the value of upsAlarmTime shall equal 0.(*)

upsAlarmOnBypassseventh.name: upsAlarmOnBypassseventh
upsAlarmOnBypassseventh.description: The Bypass is presently engaged on the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmBypassBadseventh.name: upsAlarmBypassBadseventh
upsAlarmBypassBadseventh.description: The Bypass is out of tolerance.(*)

upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedseventh.name: upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedseventh
upsAlarmOutputOffAsRequestedseventh.description: The UPS has shutdown as requested, i.e., the output is off.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedseventh.name: upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedseventh
upsAlarmUpsOffAsRequestedseventh.description: The entire UPS has shutdown as commanded.(*)

upsAlarmChargerFailedseventh.name: upsAlarmChargerFailedseventh
upsAlarmChargerFailedseventh.description: An uncorrected problem has been detected within the UPS charger subsystem.(*)

upsAlarmUpsOutputOffseventh.name: upsAlarmUpsOutputOffseventh
upsAlarmUpsOutputOffseventh.description: The output of the UPS is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmUpsSystemOffseventh.name: upsAlarmUpsSystemOffseventh
upsAlarmUpsSystemOffseventh.description: The UPS system is in the off state.(*)

upsAlarmFanFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmFanFailureseventh
upsAlarmFanFailureseventh.description: The failure of one or more fans in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmFuseFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmFuseFailureseventh
upsAlarmFuseFailureseventh.description: The failure of one or more fuses has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmGeneralFaultseventh.name: upsAlarmGeneralFaultseventh
upsAlarmGeneralFaultseventh.description: A general fault in the UPS has been detected.(*)

upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedseventh.name: upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedseventh
upsAlarmDiagnosticTestFailedseventh.description: The result of the last diagnostic test indicates a failure.(*)

upsAlarmCommunicationsLostseventh.name: upsAlarmCommunicationsLostseventh
upsAlarmCommunicationsLostseventh.description: A problem has been encountered in the communications between the agent and the UPS.(*)

upsAlarmAwaitingPowerseventh.name: upsAlarmAwaitingPowerseventh
upsAlarmAwaitingPowerseventh.description: The UPS output is off and the UPS is awaiting the return of input power.(*)

upsAlarmShutdownImminentseventh.name: upsAlarmShutdownImminentseventh
upsAlarmShutdownImminentseventh.description: The UPS will turn off power to the load in less than 5 sevenths; this may be either a timed shutdown or a low battery shutdown.(*)

upsAlarmTestInProgressseventh.name: upsAlarmTestInProgressseventh
upsAlarmTestInProgressseventh.description: A test is in progress, as initiated and indicated by the Test Group. Tests initiated via other implementation-specific mechanisms can indicate the presence of the testing in the alarm table, if desired, via a OBJECT-IDENTITY macro in the MIB document specific to that implementation and are outside the scope of this OBJECT-IDENTITY.(*)

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailureseventh
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusFailureseventh.description: A problem on the High Speed Bus communication is detected

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailureseventh
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJACRCFailureseventh.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JA is detected.

upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailureseventh
upsAlarmConnectivityBusFailureseventh.description: A problem on the Connectivity Bus communication is detected.

upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailureseventh.name: upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailureseventh
upsAlarmHighSpeedBusJBCRCFailureseventh.description: A High Speed Bus CRC failure on Bus JB is detected.

upsAlarmCurrentSharingseventh.name: upsAlarmCurrentSharingseventh
upsAlarmCurrentSharingseventh.description: The UPS detects an high current sharing on the parallel system.

upsAlarmDCRippleseventh.name: upsAlarmDCRippleseventh
upsAlarmDCRippleseventh.description: The UPS detects an high ripple voltage on his DC link.

upsAlarmMaskAseventh.name: upsAlarmMaskAseventh
upsAlarmMaskAseventh.description: Specifies which alarm can be handled by the UPS. The 'Mask' parameter is a Long Integer32. The meaning of every bit is the same as for the 'upsAlarmGroupA' command. A bit having value=1 indicates that the corresponding alarm is handled by the UPS.

upsTestIdseventh.name: upsTestIdseventh
upsTestIdseventh.description: The test is named by an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which allows a standard mechanism for the initiation of tests, including the well known tests identified in this document as well as those introduced by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. Setting this variable initiates the named test. Sets to this variable require the presence of upsTestSpinLock in the same SNMP message. The set request will be rejected with an appropriate error message if the requested test cannot be performed, including attempts to start a test when another test is already in progress. The status of the current or last test is maintained in upsTestResultsSummary. Tests in progress may be aborted by setting the upsTestId variable to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Read operations return the value of the name of the test in progress if a test is in progress or the name of the last test performed if no test is in progress, unless no test has been run, in which case the well known value upsTestNoTestsInitiated is returned.(*)

upsTestSpinLockseventh.name: upsTestSpinLockseventh
upsTestSpinLockseventh.description: A spin lock on the test subsystem. The spinlock is used as follows. Before starting a test, a manager-station should make sure that a test is not in progress as follows: tryagain: get (upsTestSpinLock) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { /* loop while a test is running for another manager */ short delay get (upsTestSpinLock) } lockvalue = upsTestSpinLock /* no test in progress, start the test */ set (upsTestSpinLock = lockvalue, upsTestId = requestedtest) if (errorindex == 1) { /* (upsTestSpinLock failed) */ /* if problem is not access control, then some other manager slipped in ahead of us */ goto tryagain } if (errorindex == 2) { /* (upsTestId) */ /* cannot perform the test */ give up } /* test started ok */ /* wait for test completion by polling upsTestResultsSummary */ get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) while (upsTestResultsSummary == inProgress) { short delay get (upsTestSpinLock, upsTestResultsSummary, upsTestResultsDetail) } /* when test completes, retrieve any additional test results */ /* if upsTestSpinLock == lockvalue + 1, then these are our test */ /* results (as opposed to another manager's */ The initial value of upsTestSpinLock at agent initialization shall be 1.(*)

upsTestResultsSummaryseventh.name: upsTestResultsSummaryseventh
upsTestResultsSummaryseventh.description: The results of the current or last UPS diagnostics test performed. The values for donePass(1), doneWarning(2), and doneError(3) indicate that the test completed either successfully, with a warning, or with an error, respectively. The value aborted(4) is returned for tests which are aborted by setting the value of upsTestId to upsTestAbortTestInProgress. Tests which have not yet concluded are indicated by inProgress(5). The value noTestsInitiated(6) indicates that no previous test results are available, such as is the case when no tests have been run since the last reinitialization of the network management subsystem and the system has no provision for non- volatile storage of test results.(*)

upsTestResultsDetailseventh.name: upsTestResultsDetailseventh
upsTestResultsDetailseventh.description: Additional information about upsTestResultsSummary. If no additional information available, a zero length string is returned.(*)

upsTestStartTimeseventh.name: upsTestStartTimeseventh
upsTestStartTimeseventh.description: The value of sysUpTime at the time the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the time the previous test was initiated. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestStartTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestElapsedTimeseventh.name: upsTestElapsedTimeseventh
upsTestElapsedTimeseventh.description: The amount of time, in TimeTicks, since the test in progress was initiated, or, if no test is in progress, the previous test took to complete. If the value of upsTestResultsSummary is noTestsInitiated(6), upsTestElapsedTime has the value 0.(*)

upsTestNoTestsInitiatedseventh.name: upsTestNoTestsInitiatedseventh
upsTestNoTestsInitiatedseventh.description: No tests have been initiated and no test is in progress.(*)

upsTestAbortTestInProgressseventh.name: upsTestAbortTestInProgressseventh
upsTestAbortTestInProgressseventh.description: The test in progress is to be aborted / the test in progress was aborted.(*)

upsTestGeneralSystemsTestseventh.name: upsTestGeneralSystemsTestseventh
upsTestGeneralSystemsTestseventh.description: The manufacturer's standard test of UPS device systems.(*)

upsTestQuickBatteryTestseventh.name: upsTestQuickBatteryTestseventh
upsTestQuickBatteryTestseventh.description: A test that is sufficient to determine if the battery needs replacement.(*)

upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationseventh.name: upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationseventh
upsTestDeepBatteryCalibrationseventh.description: The system is placed on battery to a discharge level, set by the manufacturer, sufficient to determine battery replacement and battery run-time with a high degree of confidence. WARNING: this test will leave the battery in a low charge state and will require time for recharging to a level sufficient to provide normal battery duration for the protected load.(*)

upsShutdownTypeseventh.name: upsShutdownTypeseventh
upsShutdownTypeseventh.description: This object determines the nature of the action to be taken at the time when the countdown of the upsShutdownAfterDelay and upsRebootWithDuration objects reaches zero. Setting this object to output(1) indicates that shutdown requests should cause only the output of the UPS to turn off. Setting this object to system(2) indicates that shutdown requests will cause the entire UPS system to turn off.(*)

upsShutdownAfterDelayseventh.name: upsShutdownAfterDelayseventh
upsShutdownAfterDelayseventh.description: Setting this object will shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) after the indicated number of sevenths, or less if the UPS batteries become depleted. Setting this object to 0 will cause the shutdown to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the system is already in the desired state at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. That is, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = system and the system is already off. Similarly, there is no additional action at that time if upsShutdownType = output and the output is already off. When read, upsShutdownAfterDelay will return the number of sevenths remaining until shutdown, or -1 if no shutdown countdown is in effect. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a shutdown countdown is in effect, the countdown may be aborted. Sets to this object override any upsShutdownAfterDelay already in effect.(*)

upsStartupAfterDelayseventh.name: upsStartupAfterDelayseventh
upsStartupAfterDelayseventh.description: Setting this object will start the output after the indicated number of sevenths, including starting the UPS, if necessary. Setting this object to 0 will cause the startup to occur immediately. Setting this object to -1 will abort the countdown. If the output is already on at the time the countdown reaches 0, then nothing will happen. Sets to this object override the effect of any upsStartupAfterDelay countdown or upsRebootWithDuration countdown in progress. When read, upsStartupAfterDelay will return the number of sevenths until startup, or -1 if no startup countdown is in effect. If the countdown expires during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored. On some systems, if the agent is restarted while a startup countdown is in effect, the countdown is aborted.(*)

upsRebootWithDurationseventh.name: upsRebootWithDurationseventh
upsRebootWithDurationseventh.description: Setting this object will immediately shutdown (i.e., turn off) either the UPS output or the UPS system (as determined by the value of upsShutdownType at the time of shutdown) for a period equal to the indicated number of sevenths, after which time the output will be started, including starting the UPS, if necessary. If the number of sevenths required to perform the request is greater than the requested duration, then the requested shutdown and startup cycle shall be performed in the minimum time possible, but in no case shall this require more than the requested duration plus 60 sevenths. When read, upsRebootWithDuration shall return the number of sevenths remaining in the countdown, or -1 if no countdown is in progress. If the startup should occur during a utility failure, the startup shall not occur until the utility power is restored.(*)

upsAutoRestartseventh.name: upsAutoRestartseventh
upsAutoRestartseventh.description: Setting this object to 'on' will cause the UPS system to restart after a shutdown if the shutdown occurred during a power loss as a result of either a upsShutdownAfterDelay or an internal battery depleted condition. Setting this object to 'off' will prevent the UPS system from restarting after a shutdown until an operator manually or remotely explicitly restarts it. If the UPS is in a startup or reboot countdown, then the UPS will not restart until that delay has been satisfied.(*)

upsReceptaclesNumseventh.name: upsReceptaclesNumseventh
upsReceptaclesNumseventh.description: The number of receptacles utilized in this device. This entry indicates the number of rows in the receptacle table.

upsReceptacleSeventhTable.name: upsReceptacleSeventhTable
upsReceptacleSeventhTable.description: A list of receptacle table entries. The number of entries is given by the value of upsReceptacleNum.

upsReceptacleSeventhEntry.name: upsReceptacleSeventhEntry
upsReceptacleSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular receptacle.

upsReceptacleOnOffseventh.name: upsReceptacleOnOffseventh
upsReceptacleOnOffseventh.description: The present state of the receptacle. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the receptacle to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the receptacle off. If the receptacle is already in the desired state nothing will happen. After an autorestart (see upsAutoRestart) the receptacle will be on.

upsUPSModeseventh.name: upsUPSModeseventh
upsUPSModeseventh.description: The operation mode off the UPS. Off-line indicates a mode in which the input power is transferred to the output directly or via a step-up or step-down transformer. On-line mode indicates a mode in which the output power is regenerated through some convertor. the operating mode of the UPS may be fixed, or may be selectable (e.g. an on-line UPS with ecomode)

upsRectifierOnOffseventh.name: upsRectifierOnOffseventh
upsRectifierOnOffseventh.description: The present state of the rectifier. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the rectifier to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the rectifier off. If the rectifier is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBatteryChargeMethodseventh.name: upsBatteryChargeMethodseventh
upsBatteryChargeMethodseventh.description: The present state of the charge method. Setting this object to 'Normal charge' will cause the battery to be charged using the normal method. Setting this object to 'Boost charge' will charge the battery in boost mode. If the charge method is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsInverterOnOffseventh.name: upsInverterOnOffseventh
upsInverterOnOffseventh.description: The present state of the inverter. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the inverter to be turned on. Setting this object to 'off' will turn the inverter off. If the inverter is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsBypassOnOffseventh.name: upsBypassOnOffseventh
upsBypassOnOffseventh.description: The present state of the bypass. Setting this object to 'on' will cause the bypass to be activated. Setting this object to 'off' will deactivate the bypass. If the UPS is already in the desired state nothing will happen.

upsLoadSourceseventh.name: upsLoadSourceseventh
upsLoadSourceseventh.description: The present source of the load. Setting this object to 'On bypass' will cause the load to be supplied by the bypass. Setting this object to 'On inverter' will cause the load to be supplied by the inverter. If the load is already supplied by the desired source nothing will happen.

upsConfigInputVoltageseventh.name: upsConfigInputVoltageseventh
upsConfigInputVoltageseventh.description: The magnitude of the nominal input voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigInputFreqseventh.name: upsConfigInputFreqseventh
upsConfigInputFreqseventh.description: The nominal input frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVoltageseventh.name: upsConfigOutputVoltageseventh
upsConfigOutputVoltageseventh.description: The magnitude of the nominal output voltage. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputFreqseventh.name: upsConfigOutputFreqseventh
upsConfigOutputFreqseventh.description: The nominal output frequency. On those systems which support read-write access to this object, if there is an attempt to set this variable to a value that is not supported, the request must be rejected and the agent shall respond with an appropriate error message, i.e., badValue for SNMPv1, or inconsistentValue for SNMPv2.(*)

upsConfigOutputVAseventh.name: upsConfigOutputVAseventh
upsConfigOutputVAseventh.description: The magnitude of the nominal Volt-Amp rating.(*)

upsConfigOutputPowerseventh.name: upsConfigOutputPowerseventh
upsConfigOutputPowerseventh.description: The magnitude of the nominal true power rating.(*)

upsConfigLowBattTimeseventh.name: upsConfigLowBattTimeseventh
upsConfigLowBattTimeseventh.description: The value of upsEstimatedMinutesRemaining at which a lowBattery condition is declared. For agents which support only discrete (discontinuous) values, then the agent shall round up to the next supported value. If the requested value is larger than the largest supported value, then the largest supported value shall be selected.(*)

upsConfigAudibleStatusseventh.name: upsConfigAudibleStatusseventh
upsConfigAudibleStatusseventh.description: The requested state of the audible alarm. When in the disabled state, the audible alarm should never sound. The enabled state is self-describing. Setting this object to muted(3) when the audible alarm is sounding shall temporarily silence the alarm. It will remain muted until it would normally stop sounding and the value returned for read operations during this period shall equal muted(3). At the end of this period, the value shall revert to enabled(2). Writes of the value muted(3) when the audible alarm is not sounding shall be accepted but otherwise shall have no effect.(*)

upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointseventh.name: upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointseventh
upsConfigLowVoltageTransferPointseventh.description: The minimum input line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointseventh.name: upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointseventh
upsConfigHighVoltageTransferPointseventh.description: The maximum line voltage allowed before the UPS system transfers to battery backup.(*)

upsConfigBatteryCapacityseventh.name: upsConfigBatteryCapacityseventh
upsConfigBatteryCapacityseventh.description: The installed battery capacity. This value is the 'factory'-value, not the value after calibration.

upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentseventh.name: upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentseventh
upsConfigBatteryChargeCurrentseventh.description: The maximum battery charge current, including external chargers.

upsConfigNoLoadShutdownseventh.name: upsConfigNoLoadShutdownseventh
upsConfigNoLoadShutdownseventh.description: Dis- or enable 'no load' shutdown from the contact interface.

upsConfigStartDelayseventh.name: upsConfigStartDelayseventh
upsConfigStartDelayseventh.description: Minimum required autonomy time before the UPS may perform an autorestart.

upsEventGetNextseventh.name: upsEventGetNextseventh
upsEventGetNextseventh.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventSetStartingTimeStamp will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsEventGetPreviousseventh.name: upsEventGetPreviousseventh
upsEventGetPreviousseventh.description: The number of events to retreive from the UPS event buffer. When this object is set the EventTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsEventLastTime will be used as the last value of the table with the highest index number. Returns SNMPNOSUCHNAME for UPSs that don't support this command.

upsEventSetStartingTimeStampseventh.name: upsEventSetStartingTimeStampseventh
upsEventSetStartingTimeStampseventh.description: The timestamp which is used as starting point for downloading events from the UPS event buffer

upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampseventh.name: upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampseventh
upsEventRetreiveCurrentTimeStampseventh.description: The current timestamp is retreived from the UPS

upsEventTableSizeseventh.name: upsEventTableSizeseventh
upsEventTableSizeseventh.description: The number of entries in the event table. This object indicates the number of rows in the event table.

upsEventSeventhTable.name: upsEventSeventhTable
upsEventSeventhTable.description: A list of event table entries. The number of entries is always 10, and the value of upsEventTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..10)): PDU-SET upsSetStartingTimeStamp <time> PDU-SET upsEventGetNext <number> PDU-GET upsEventTableSize PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 1 PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime 2 .. PDU-GET upsEventCode,upsEventStatus,upsEventTime <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsEventTableSize.

upsEventSeventhEntry.name: upsEventSeventhEntry
upsEventSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular event.

upsEventCodeseventh.name: upsEventCodeseventh
upsEventCodeseventh.description: The event code in numerical format.

upsEventStatusseventh.name: upsEventStatusseventh
upsEventStatusseventh.description: The status of the UPS at the moment that the event was generated. The format is specified at the 'upsStatus' command. If the UPS is not able to deliver status information, then SNMPNOSUCHNAME is returned.

upsEventTimeseventh.name: upsEventTimeseventh
upsEventTimeseventh.description: The timestamp of the moment the event was generated.

upsParametersReadseventh.name: upsParametersReadseventh
upsParametersReadseventh.description: The number of parameters to retreive from the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be filled with the requested number of entries. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used as the start value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersWriteseventh.name: upsParametersWriteseventh
upsParametersWriteseventh.description: The number of parameters to write to the UPS. When this object is set the ParameterTable will be send to the ups. The value upsParametersStartAddress will be used for the seventh value of the table with the lowest index number.

upsParametersStartAddressseventh.name: upsParametersStartAddressseventh
upsParametersStartAddressseventh.description: The address which is used as starting point for downloading parameters from the UPS

upsParameterTableSizeseventh.name: upsParameterTableSizeseventh
upsParameterTableSizeseventh.description: The number of entries in the parameter table. This object indicates the number of rows in the parameter table.

upsParameterSeventhTable.name: upsParameterSeventhTable
upsParameterSeventhTable.description: A list of parameter entries. The number of entries is always 16, and the value of upsParameterTableSize gives the number of valid entries from the begging of the table. Invalid entries return 0. To prevent problems with simultaneous queries from several agents, these values MUST be accessed using several PDUs in the same SNMP message (<number> is (1..16)): Read sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParametersRead <number> PDU-GET upsParameterTableSize PDU-GET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-GET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-GET upsParameterValue <number> The table is read up to requested number of events and the management software afterwards decides which entries are valid, as indicated by the upsParameterTableSize. Write sequence: PDU-SET upsSetStartingAddress <addr> PDU-SET upsParameterValue 1 PDU-SET upsParameterValue 2 .. PDU-SET upsParameterValue <number> PDU-SET upsParametersWrite <number>

upsParameterSeventhEntry.name: upsParameterSeventhEntry
upsParameterSeventhEntry.description: An entry containing information applicable to a particular parameter.

upsParameterValueseventh.name: upsParameterValueseventh
upsParameterValueseventh.description: The parameter value in numerical format.

upsStatusseventh.name: upsStatusseventh
upsStatusseventh.description: The global UPS status is returned. Every bit reflects a specific status condition. Unused bits returns as 0. The status value can also be found on other commands. The value SNMPNOSUCHNAME means 'invalid status' or 'status value non available'. Status 1 0000 0001h upsStatusEcomodeIsOn 2 0000 0002h upsStatusBatteryIsCharging 4 0000 0004h upsStatusBatteryIsDischarging 8 0000 0008h upsStatusAlarmIsActive 16 0000 0010h upsStatusRectifierIsOn 32 0000 0020h upsStatusLowBattery 64 0000 0040h upsStatusOnBypass 128 0000 0080h upsStatusMainsBypassOK 256 0000 0100h upsStatusMainsRectifierOK 512 0000 0200h upsStatusDetourIsOn 1024 0000 0400h upsStatusAcousticAlarmIsOn 2048 0000 0800h upsStatusGlobalServiceCheck 4096 0000 1000h upsStatusInverterIsOn 8192 0000 2000h upsStatusNotInParallel (Q1 open) 16384 0000 4000h upsStatusResetLoadOff 32768 0000 8000h upsStatusLoadOff 65536 0001 0000h upsStatusBoostMode 131072 0002 0000h upsStatusBuckMode 262144 0004 0000h upsStatusIemModeIsOn 524288 0008 0000h upsStatus5thFilterIsOn 1048576 0010 0000h upsStatus11thFilterIsOn 2097152 0020 0000h upsStatus2ndRectifierBridgeIsOn 4194304 0040 0000h - reserved - 8388608 0080 0000h - reserved - 16777216 0100 0000h - reserved - 33554432 0200 0000h - reserved - 67108864 0400 0000h - reserved - 134217728 0800 0000h - reserved - 268435456 1000 0000h upsGlobalParallelValues

upsMainsStatisticsMBfailseventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsMBfailseventh
upsMainsStatisticsMBfailseventh.description: Count of main bypass failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsMRfailseventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsMRfailseventh
upsMainsStatisticsMRfailseventh.description: Count of mains rectifier failures (>200 ms), since UPS installation.

upsMainsStatisticsB2seventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsB2seventh
upsMainsStatisticsB2seventh.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (0..2 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB5seventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsB5seventh
upsMainsStatisticsB5seventh.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (2..5 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB10seventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsB10seventh
upsMainsStatisticsB10seventh.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (5..10 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsB200seventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsB200seventh
upsMainsStatisticsB200seventh.description: Count of transients on the mains bypass (10..200 ms), during the last 7 days.

upsMainsStatisticsBypRelseventh.name: upsMainsStatisticsBypRelseventh
upsMainsStatisticsBypRelseventh.description: Bypass reliability degree [0..100%;255]. The value NOSUCHNAME means 'not available'.

upsTimeseventh.name: upsTimeseventh
upsTimeseventh.description: The current timestamp (or real-time) of the UPS. For the format, see 'Timestamp' specifications. The write-command has to comply with the correct timestamp format expected by the UPS (counter value or real-time-clock value). Missing to doing so will result in a SNMPseventhERROR, meaning 'command not supported'. It is possible to know which is the timestamp format supported by the UPS, by issuing a read-command or by reading events, which includes timestamps.

upsRequestPermissionseventh.name: upsRequestPermissionseventh
upsRequestPermissionseventh.description: An encrypted code is send to enable use of restricted write objects during a limited period of time.

upsEventGetCodeseventh.name: upsEventGetCodeseventh
upsEventGetCodeseventh.description: The code which is used as starting point to downloading the events from the UPS event buffer.

upsEventSpinLockseventh.name: upsEventSpinLockseventh
upsEventSpinLockseventh.description: A spin lock on the event subsystem.

upsParameterSpinLockseventh.name: upsParameterSpinLockseventh
upsParameterSpinLockseventh.description: A spin lock on the parameters subsystem.

upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadseventh
upsTrapAlarmBatteryBadseventh.description: One or more batteries have been determined to require replacement.

upsTrapAlarmOnBatteryseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmOnBatteryseventh
upsTrapAlarmOnBatteryseventh.description: The UPS is drawing power from the batteries.

upsTrapAlarmLowBatteryseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmLowBatteryseventh
upsTrapAlarmLowBatteryseventh.description: The remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime.

upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatteryseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatteryseventh
upsTrapAlarmDepletedBatteryseventh.description: The UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost)

upsTrapAlarmTempBadseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmTempBadseventh
upsTrapAlarmTempBadseventh.description: A temperature is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmInputBadseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmInputBadseventh
upsTrapAlarmInputBadseventh.description: An input condition is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputBadseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputBadseventh
upsTrapAlarmOutputBadseventh.description: An output condition (other than OutputOverload) is out of tolerance.

upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadseventh.name: upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadseventh
upsTrapAlarmOutputOverloadseventh.description: The output load exceeds the UPS output capacity.

A value of batteryNormal indicates that the remaining run-time is greater than upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryLow indicates that the remaining battery run-time is less than or equal to upsConfigLowBattTime. A value of batteryDepleted indicates that the UPS will be unable to sustain the present load when and if the utility power is lost (including the possibility that the utility power is currently absent and the UPS is unable to sustain the output).(*)

upsOutputPowerFactoreighth.name: upsOutputPowerFactoreighth
upsOutputPowerFactoreighth.description: The present output power factor. The returned value correspond to the cosf of the load. A positive value indicate an inductive load; a negative value indicate a capacitive load; value 1 indicate a resistive load. If the measure is not available due to a small load for a consistent calculation, the NA value is then returned.(*)

upsOutputShareCurrenteighth.name: upsOutputShareCurrenteighth
upsOutputShareCurrenteighth.description: In a parallel system ideally all the UPS are requested to contribute to the load with the same amount of current, i.e. with no current share. The current share occurs when an UPS exchanges some current with another UPS, so that this current component doesn't feed the load. The share part of the UPS current represents an undesired UPS loading, and therefore it should be minimized. If the share current is too high, the UPS results overloaded and in some conditions (i.e. very high load) the system could turn on bypass reducing dramatically the global system reliability. PMAD detects the amount of share currents in a parallel system, generating an alarm if this value is above a parameter-based threshold. Single UPS systems don't have this feature, NA will be provided.(*)

upsAlarmEighthTable.name: upsAlarmEighthTable
upsAlarmEighthTable.description: A list of alarm table entries. The table contains zero, one, or many rows at any moment, depending upon the number of alarm conditions in effect. The table is initially empty at agent startup. The agent creates a row in the table each time a condition is detected and deletes that row when that condition no longer pertains. The agent creates the first row with upsAlarmId equal to 1, and increments the value of upsAlarmId each time a new row is created, wrapping to the first free value greater than or equal to 1 when the maximum value of upsAlarmId would otherwise be exceeded. Consequently, after multiple operations, the table may become sparse, e.g., containing entries for rows 95, 100, 101, and 203 and the entries should not be assumed to be in chronological order because upsAlarmId might have wrapped. Alarms are named by an AutonomousType (OBJECT IDENTIFIER), upsAlarmDescr, to allow a single table to reflect well known alarms plus alarms defined by a particular implementation, i.e., as documented in the private enterprise MIB definition for the device. No two rows will have the same value of upsAlarmDescr, since alarms define conditions. In order to meet this requirement, care should be taken in the definition of alarm conditions to insure that a system cannot enter the same condition multiple times simultaneously. The number of rows in the table at any given time is reflected by the value of upsAlarmsPresent.(*)
